WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.960
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes we look at the way things are and we think that's the only way they

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:12.880
[Amit Varma]: can be. Maybe we look at the lines on a map and they seem to tell us something

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:16.520
[Amit Varma]: real about the world until we realize that we're looking at a map from 200

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:20.440
[Amit Varma]: years ago and there are different lines now. Sometimes we look at a person who is

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:24.480
[Amit Varma]: 25 years old and we make judgments about that person and assume that what they

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:29.200
[Amit Varma]: are is all they will ever be and then we look at them 25 years later and they are

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:32.860
[Amit Varma]: someone else. These fixed ways of looking at the world happens a lot in

00:00:32.860 --> 00:00:36.960
[Amit Varma]: industries, in organizations and it happened in the world of Indian media.

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:41.600
[Amit Varma]: Once upon a time everyone who ran our big media houses knew each other, moved

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:45.520
[Amit Varma]: in the same circles, looked the same, looked at the world the same way. Their

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:49.920
[Amit Varma]: gaze was limited but everyone was so used to that way of looking that there

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:53.200
[Amit Varma]: seemed to be no other way to see the world. It may have stayed that way

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:57.240
[Amit Varma]: forever or changed at a glacial pace but then the internet came around and

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:02.400
[Amit Varma]: technology empowered people everywhere and today we realize how limited that

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:07.240
[Amit Varma]: gaze was. Big media based out of Delhi looked at the world the way a privileged

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:11.840
[Amit Varma]: North Indian man would and that point of view misses everything important about

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:17.920
[Amit Varma]: this country. But thankfully as India is changing so is our media.

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:24.760
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:30.200
[Unknown]: behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:36.080
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. My guest today is Dhania Rajendran, founder

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:40.320
[Amit Varma]: and editor of the News Minute. Dhania grew up in Palakkad in Kerala, not a

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.320
[Amit Varma]: place that has produced too many media superstars. She got into journalism a

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:48.560
[Amit Varma]: couple of decades ago and spent a few years in Times Now where she rose to be

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:52.640
[Amit Varma]: Bureau Chief for all of South India. Working in what she now describes as a

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:57.800
[Amit Varma]: toxic newsroom, she grew frustrated by the homogeneous gaze of her editors in

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:02.200
[Amit Varma]: Delhi. It was a gaze centered around North India. Stories from the South were

00:02:02.200 --> 00:02:06.320
[Amit Varma]: not given importance. She would not only have to produce great stories, she would

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:10.440
[Amit Varma]: also have to market them to her bosses to convince them that these were worth

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:14.440
[Amit Varma]: carrying. Another gaze that was a problem was the male gaze. Even in an

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:18.560
[Amit Varma]: industry that had many women reporters, every story was looked at from a male

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:22.640
[Amit Varma]: point of view. When Dhania eventually struck out on her own, she decided to

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:26.880
[Amit Varma]: fight these gazes, to build diverse newsrooms with people of different

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:30.680
[Amit Varma]: genders, castes, and class backgrounds. She walked the talk in building the

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:34.680
[Amit Varma]: News Minute, which in my opinion does some of the finest journalism in this

00:02:34.680 --> 00:02:38.840
[Amit Varma]: country. They break stories no one else goes near, and they look at stories

00:02:38.840 --> 00:02:43.120
[Amit Varma]: through a variety of different lenses. Dhania was kind enough to open up to me

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:47.200
[Amit Varma]: about her journey so far and her thoughts on Indian media. But before we

00:02:47.200 --> 00:02:51.200
[Amit Varma]: get to the conversation, I want to make an appeal. If you agree with me that this

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:55.360
[Amit Varma]: kind of brave journalism is what India needs, then support it not just with

00:02:55.360 --> 00:03:00.520
[Amit Varma]: words, but with actions. Head on over to the newsminute.com slash support us, the

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:03.960
[Amit Varma]: link will be in the show notes, and help them out with whatever monetary

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:08.160
[Amit Varma]: contribution you can afford. All of us who crave good journalism, let us not

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:13.280
[Amit Varma]: take it for granted. It exists despite the odds, and it needs us to keep

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:17.200
[Amit Varma]: existing. So let's do our bit. And I'm sure you'll agree with me about what a

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:21.920
[Amit Varma]: great cause the News Minute is, after you hear my conversation with Dhania. But

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:25.280
[Amit Varma]: first, let's take a quick commercial break.

