[Amit Varma]: at ctqcompounds.com and use the code UNSEEN. Up-level yourself.

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:01.680
[Amit Varma]: Dhaniya, welcome to The Scene and The Unseen. Thank you, Amit. It's a pleasure

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:05.720
[Amit Varma]: being here. Yeah, I got to tell all my listeners that I'm recording in this

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:08.920
[Amit Varma]: Bangalore studio, which is on the second floor and Dhaniya has a broken foot and

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:13.800
[Amit Varma]: was kind enough to actually come here with the broken foot. So I'm very

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:17.600
[Amit Varma]: grateful for that, though it would seem from the body of your work that

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:21.120
[Amit Varma]: you're deeply committed to everything you take up. So at one level, also not

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:26.040
[Amit Varma]: surprised. So how did your foot break? So this is the first fracture I've got in

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:32.760
[Guest]: my life. I am a cat person, I mean I'm a pet person. I have two cats at

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:37.240
[Guest]: home and there are stray cats which come sleep and go off. So one stray cat fought

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:41.920
[Guest]: with my house cat and I ran behind them and I hit something. I don't know what, I

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:46.120
[Guest]: can't remember properly, but my toe fractured. And so I've been like this for

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:49.640
[Guest]: three weeks. The first time actually I'm stepping out, other than to see the

00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:55.320
[Amit Varma]: doctor. Wow, okay. So let's kind of start at the beginning and tell me

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:57.840
[Amit Varma]: where you grew up, where were you born, where did you grow up, what were your

00:05:57.840 --> 00:06:04.320
[Guest]: young years like? So I'm from Palakkad in Kerala. I mean at those times it was

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:08.000
[Guest]: called Palghat and then it was changed to Palakkad. I did my schooling in

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.560
[Guest]: college in Palakkad itself. I studied in a convent school called Karnike

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:17.080
[Guest]: Mada Convent and I studied in a government school called Government Victoria. I have

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:26.240
[Guest]: had a very active life in Palakkad in the sense that, I know a lot of people

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:29.880
[Guest]: say that they were rebellious in their childhood. I'm not saying it just for

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:35.800
[Guest]: being fashionable, I actually was. And in the convent that I studied, from the

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:41.040
[Guest]: nuns to the teachers to everybody, they were really, I think they molded me to a

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:44.800
[Guest]: large extent. Of course other than my parents and my friends, but my teachers

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:50.240
[Guest]: and my nuns and the ones who ran the school and then college came. So I don't

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:54.240
[Guest]: know if you know much about how the education system is in Kerala, but in a

00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:59.800
[Guest]: convent it is much more disciplined, you know, you have classes properly. The

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:02.040
[Guest]: reason I am saying is, if it's a government school there could be a

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:05.320
[Guest]: hartal, there could be a strike which the students call and then there won't be

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:09.000
[Guest]: class that day. So nothing like that happens in a convent. We go every day to

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.680
[Guest]: school, we go in the school bus, come back. But it was really amazing because

00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:17.280
[Guest]: in Kerala you have this very vibrant system of extracurricular activities. For

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:21.800
[Guest]: example, from your childhood you will have a school level competition, then

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:26.840
[Guest]: sub-district, then district and state. So it's like an entire year is charted for

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:31.040
[Guest]: you just for your extracurricular activities. So in that I was into

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:37.960
[Guest]: elocution, theater, all kinds of things. Like I was into Sanskrit speech because

00:07:37.960 --> 00:07:41.400
[Guest]: it's easy to get points for that. Nobody can speak five minutes in Sanskrit

00:07:41.400 --> 00:07:44.800
[Guest]: continuously. I could manage to speak gibberish in Sanskrit for five minutes.

00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:50.400
[Guest]: So I used to win that and Sanskrit drama, lots of things. It was fun and I think by

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:56.280
[Guest]: the end of school, which is 8th, 9th and 10th, I was into science. I keep changing my

00:07:56.280 --> 00:08:00.320
[Guest]: interest. So I was a young scientist of India. There's a competition which

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:04.760
[Guest]: happens where Professor Yashpal Sharma used to be one of the mentors. So I was

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:09.680
[Guest]: one of those young scientists of India and in Palakkad, a small town, like if a

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:13.000
[Guest]: kid does something, immediately you're under Manorama or Mathrubhumi the next day.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.480
[Guest]: And my father is sort of pushy also. So every time people used to meet me and

00:08:17.480 --> 00:08:22.040
[Guest]: say, oh you will become a scientist. So I was like, absolutely no. If you expect me

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:25.600
[Guest]: to do something, I will not do that. I did not tell my dad I went to this

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:29.640
[Guest]: Government Victoria College. My father wanted me to join another girls college

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:33.160
[Guest]: which was more disciplined, nice. Not because it's a girls college, but because it's

00:08:33.160 --> 00:08:36.640
[Guest]: more disciplined. But he was not against me going to the Government College. I

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:40.480
[Guest]: went there and I took the form and I filled Commerce. So everybody thought I'll

00:08:40.480 --> 00:08:44.320
[Guest]: become a scientist. I definitely did not have the brains to become a scientist. I

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:48.320
[Guest]: mean, you know in school when you go for a competition and you win it, you can't

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:52.280
[Guest]: equate that to actually becoming a scientist. So I know my capability and I

00:08:52.280 --> 00:08:55.320
[Guest]: know people are expecting too much out of me. So I'm like, screw it, I'm not gonna

00:08:55.320 --> 00:08:58.600
[Guest]: become a scientist or I'm not even going to try. So I went into Commerce, it was

00:08:58.600 --> 00:09:03.760
[Guest]: the easiest. And five years in college was very different from the school

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:08.920
[Guest]: because here is a college which is highly political. Like every second day

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:13.240
[Guest]: there'll be a strike, they will shut down class. So the first one year I observed

00:09:13.240 --> 00:09:17.920
[Guest]: everything and then I got into student politics and the next four years were

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:24.920
[Guest]: really like, it changed my life a lot also. Like how I perceive things, how

00:09:24.920 --> 00:09:29.040
[Guest]: a leader should be or you know the kind of resistance that you face. For example,

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:33.080
[Guest]: when you study in a convent school and there are like 10 smart kids, you give

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:35.560
[Guest]: everything off to them easily, right. There's a competition, you immediately say

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:38.120
[Guest]: okay you go for dance, you go for elocution. There is not really any

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:42.000
[Guest]: democracy there. But when you come to a college and there are kids from all

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.600
[Guest]: sections of society and especially the SFI was very powerful, there's a lot of

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:50.120
[Guest]: resistance. They don't want your English-speaking convent kids to just come

00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:54.320
[Guest]: over, come and take over everything. So I faced that resistance also. At that point

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:58.480
[Guest]: of time, I didn't appreciate that resistance. But now when I think back, I

00:09:58.480 --> 00:10:03.760
[Guest]: understand where they came from. But at that time no, they were my archenemies and

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:07.600
[Guest]: so it was it was quite fun, college and school and I think that shaped me to a

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:12.760
[Amit Varma]: large extent. Did that resistance also then force you to work harder? To not, you

00:10:12.760 --> 00:10:15.680
[Amit Varma]: know, take your own skills for granted so to say but actually work harder at

00:10:15.680 --> 00:10:18.840
[Amit Varma]: whatever you did, I'm guessing the extracurricular activities or whatever.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:24.600
[Guest]: So in my case, okay I was smart in school, right. I won all these competitions. I was

00:10:24.600 --> 00:10:28.280
[Guest]: you know, there is this thing called children's prime minister which they

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:31.840
[Guest]: have in every district of Kerala. So one student wins the elocution, they become

00:10:31.840 --> 00:10:35.040
[Guest]: Jawaharlal Nehru and they're dressed up like Jawaharlal Nehru and there's an

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:39.480
[Guest]: open Jeep in which they are taken through the town and you have to

00:10:39.480 --> 00:10:42.560
[Guest]: just salute like Jawaharlal Nehru. All the school students will stand and salute.

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:47.240
[Guest]: When I do this, everybody thinks, oh my god she can do everything. I can't. I know

00:10:47.240 --> 00:10:51.960
[Guest]: exactly that my skill is only this much. People may want me to, at one point I

00:10:51.960 --> 00:10:57.720
[Guest]: thought I'll become an MBA. The second I saw the textbooks of XLRI and the

00:10:57.720 --> 00:11:02.520
[Guest]: what is it the for the entrance exam, I was like absolutely no. I will not pass

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:07.240
[Guest]: this exam. Most of my friends took science. They all went for this coaching

00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:11.720
[Guest]: classes which are terrible. They have to stay there. They have to study 20 hours I

00:11:11.720 --> 00:11:15.520
[Guest]: think. I was like this is not for me. I cannot be a doctor or an engineer

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:20.280
[Guest]: anyways and science was no-no for me. So I think from my childhood I knew what I

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:24.600
[Guest]: was capable of and so I would only push myself in that direction. I've never

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:29.280
[Guest]: tried things which I am skeptical about. Like if I think I can't do an MBA, I will

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:33.520
[Guest]: not waste even five minutes trying to study. So I was very clear about what I

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:37.200
[Guest]: can do. People can have hundred perceptions about me. Like even today

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:40.360
[Guest]: when I'm running the news minute, everybody asks me why don't you give an

00:11:40.360 --> 00:11:44.160
[Guest]: opinion. Like why don't you do a show like Shekhar Gupta does of like cut the

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:48.520
[Guest]: clutter and explain. Because I don't know most things. I may have an opinion but I

00:11:48.520 --> 00:11:51.400
[Guest]: don't think that opinion is good enough and I don't want to be thrusting that on

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:55.600
[Guest]: other people. That's the reason why I don't do it. So I am very clear on what I

00:11:55.600 --> 00:12:00.760
[Guest]: can do and what I cannot do which which has helped me quite a bit. But there are

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:04.840
[Guest]: times I wonder maybe I should have taken a chance with an MBA and led a very

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:09.520
[Guest]: peaceful life in some MNC making a lot of money and not worrying about you know

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:15.240
[Guest]: social media and stuff like that. But generally I think most of how I grew up

00:12:15.240 --> 00:12:18.800
[Guest]: and what I ended up becoming is also because my parents though they were from

00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:24.880
[Guest]: Palakkad, they were not conservative at all. I would not come back home till 8-9

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:28.000
[Guest]: in the night when I had a bike because we'll have a lot of events in college

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.680
[Guest]: school. But my brother doesn't come back by 6-6.30. My father be worried. Where is

00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:35.600
[Guest]: he? Where is he? If I don't come back they will not be worried because they know

00:12:35.600 --> 00:12:40.120
[Guest]: that I can take care of myself. And I had a boyfriend imagine in Palakkad who

00:12:40.120 --> 00:12:44.640
[Guest]: used to come home. Nobody would blink an eye. They would not ask me. But if other

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:48.560
[Guest]: girls do the same thing, everybody would be shocked and they'd be like how are you

00:12:48.560 --> 00:12:54.320
[Guest]: taking them home. My parents had no such issues. So that way they also helped me

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:59.000
[Guest]: become you know grow up in a certain way without any restrictions. Therefore that

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:04.480
[Guest]: helped. But politics in college was was also a life-altering situation I would

00:13:04.480 --> 00:13:09.880
[Guest]: say. See when I say politics I did not understand an SFI or a KSU as an ABVP

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:14.680
[Guest]: for the political party represented. That was alien to me. Like I did not know the

00:13:14.680 --> 00:13:19.520
[Guest]: BJP intricately or the Congress or the Communists. When I enter college I know a

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:23.240
[Guest]: lot of seniors who are with the KSU which is the Kerala Students Union. So my

00:13:23.240 --> 00:13:27.760
[Guest]: immediate inclination is to go with them. And then by next year I have made

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:32.760
[Guest]: friends in SFI and ABVP also. So I'm completely confused as to what to do. But

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:37.280
[Guest]: in those five years by the end by the end by the time I finished college I

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:41.040
[Guest]: decided that this is a party I don't like. I don't like the way these people

00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:45.600
[Guest]: behave. I appreciate the way the other one behaves. But by the end of it I

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:51.280
[Guest]: contested as an independent. I mean I have contested three elections. One I was

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:55.700
[Guest]: unanimous candidate of all three parties. The next one I was a candidate of two

00:13:55.700 --> 00:14:01.000
[Guest]: parties and not SFI because by then we had split. By the fifth year I got tired

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:06.280
[Guest]: of all three and I stood alone. They all had candidates against me. So for me it

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:10.640
[Guest]: has been a very, the college has been a learning experience as to you know when

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:14.440
[Guest]: you're in a situation where there is a lot of conflict, people have different

00:14:14.440 --> 00:14:19.280
[Guest]: opinions, do you have to go with the flow simply because you believed in that one

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:24.360
[Guest]: gang before you joined. So I mean I had enough friends with me who told me that

00:14:24.360 --> 00:14:27.000
[Guest]: no just whatever you believe in if you don't agree with them you don't have to

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.200
[Guest]: go with them. Even if you don't win an election it doesn't matter. But don't

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:34.240
[Guest]: have to stand with someone who you don't want to stand with. So that kind of

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:38.480
[Guest]: resilience and that kind of a thinking I think a lot of friends and my family and

00:14:38.480 --> 00:14:43.160
[Guest]: everybody around me did help. So I'm studying in Kerala when I then went to

00:14:43.160 --> 00:14:48.040
[Guest]: Tamil Nadu and I went to Karnataka. I feel like students are deprived here of

00:14:48.040 --> 00:14:53.520
[Guest]: quite a lot of things especially no campus politics. Even Kerala doesn't have

00:14:53.520 --> 00:14:58.480
[Guest]: campus politics now and even extracurricular activities is looked down

00:14:58.480 --> 00:15:02.440
[Guest]: beyond a point. Like my son is in fifth standard and there is so much of tension

00:15:02.440 --> 00:15:06.400
[Guest]: in the whatsapp group among parents as to oh my god they're coming back from

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:10.880
[Guest]: school at 3.15 when will they prepare for the exam. So my son had a big lecture

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:14.120
[Guest]: for me and my husband yesterday saying what kind of parents are you don't even

00:15:14.120 --> 00:15:18.560
[Guest]: know when my exam is. I said that's fine I mean it's not like a board exam as

00:15:18.560 --> 00:15:23.600
[Guest]: long as you have a foundation right it's okay but he's really angry with us. But I

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:27.560
[Guest]: feel like if he had studied in Kerala at least the time that I did he would have

00:15:27.560 --> 00:15:30.800
[Guest]: got so many more opportunities to do different different things. I feel like

00:15:30.800 --> 00:15:36.240
[Guest]: many other states maybe my judgment is wrong but at in the 1980s when I studied

00:15:36.240 --> 00:15:42.280
[Guest]: in 1990s I felt that Kerala gave much more opportunity for people to grow in

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:46.200
[Guest]: many different ways or at least the places I studied in. And what attracted

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:53.960
[Guest]: you to campus politics? So generally I'm a violent person in the sense that I can

00:15:53.960 --> 00:16:00.120
[Guest]: I'm very vocal and if I see something in front of me I have to give my opinion

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:04.480
[Guest]: therefore if something is happening in the college and a college union has to

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:08.480
[Guest]: decide I realize that that's where the power lies of deciding something right

00:16:08.480 --> 00:16:13.080
[Guest]: so I have to be a part of that. So my thoughts very violent also sometimes and

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:18.240
[Guest]: I mean I can tell you there's one election where we used to carry these

00:16:18.240 --> 00:16:21.840
[Guest]: pocketknives with us because there would be violence there would be actual

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:26.840
[Guest]: physical violence so it was also a little rush throughout the college thing

00:16:26.840 --> 00:16:31.360
[Guest]: but mainly because I realized it's the union that decides in a college even the

00:16:31.360 --> 00:16:34.760
[Guest]: smallest things like do you want this construction to happen here do you want

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:38.120
[Guest]: this course to come here do you want this teacher so everything the union had

00:16:38.120 --> 00:16:43.480
[Guest]: a say and therefore I felt like I had to be part of the union which is one reason

00:16:43.480 --> 00:16:47.280
[Guest]: why I was interested like I said I had no I did not identify with the political

00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:51.440
[Guest]: party or thought at that time but I did know that I want to be I want to have a

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:54.720
[Guest]: say in what happens in my college and to be part of the union then was very

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:58.600
[Amit Varma]: important. And I'm sure other people would also be in campus politics with

00:16:58.600 --> 00:17:02.160
[Amit Varma]: because of the urge that we care about the things around us we want to be part

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:05.760
[Amit Varma]: of the change right but that urge dissipates at some level the higher up

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:09.480
[Amit Varma]: you go in terms of politics like at the national level I would say that most

00:17:09.480 --> 00:17:13.240
[Amit Varma]: citizens are kind of apathetic and one reason for that might well be that power

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:16.480
[Amit Varma]: is so centralized and you don't really see a connection between your

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:20.000
[Amit Varma]: involvement and anything changing and all of that and the ways in which you

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:23.400
[Amit Varma]: are trying to make a difference today are not political ways but they are all

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:27.280
[Amit Varma]: these other ways which are perhaps even more important. Where do you think that

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:31.160
[Amit Varma]: disconnect happens that in the context of a college and what's going on there

00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:35.560
[Amit Varma]: you are a concerned citizen as it were of the college but then you come out and

00:17:35.560 --> 00:17:39.440
[Amit Varma]: at some level there is that disconnect where you are like I don't identify with

00:17:39.440 --> 00:17:43.440
[Amit Varma]: this anymore there is no point my getting into this game and I'm gonna do

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:47.040
[Amit Varma]: other stuff is there a point where the disconnect happens or is it simply that

00:17:47.040 --> 00:17:50.040
[Amit Varma]: here you've done your college and you're getting on with life and people just

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:55.200
[Guest]: move on. No see for me like I said by the end of my college years my fifth year in

00:17:55.200 --> 00:17:59.840
[Guest]: college when I stood for the chairman post for elections I did not identify

00:17:59.840 --> 00:18:04.080
[Guest]: with any party by then I did not want to stand in their panels but I'd still want

00:18:04.080 --> 00:18:06.880
[Guest]: to be part of the union and I wanted to be the chairperson of the college I

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest]: didn't want I didn't want to exit that college without becoming its chairperson

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:16.480
[Guest]: so that's a risk I took at that time and I did win the election but I think

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:22.480
[Guest]: towards the end of my college I was watching NDTV I cannot remember whether

00:18:22.480 --> 00:18:27.680
[Guest]: NDTV was a singular platform at that time or it was a it was on star I think

00:18:27.680 --> 00:18:31.520
[Guest]: they used to have this show so Deva Gowda had stepped down as Prime Minister

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:35.720
[Guest]: now my memory is very vague but I remember Rajdeep Sardesai and some I

00:18:35.720 --> 00:18:39.120
[Guest]: don't know if it was Barkha Dutt or Arnab Goswami but they were having this

00:18:39.120 --> 00:18:44.480
[Guest]: really passionate debate about Deva Gowda stepping down and why again we'll

00:18:44.480 --> 00:18:48.360
[Guest]: have an election or they were discussing about taxpayers money going down the

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:52.320
[Guest]: drain and then I thought this is actually a job I can do I mean they're

00:18:52.320 --> 00:18:56.240
[Guest]: talking for other people and maybe this is something I should do that's actually

00:18:56.240 --> 00:19:00.480
[Guest]: the first time I started looking up at journalism and I just decided that okay

00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:05.800
[Guest]: maybe this is the course I want to look at not an MBA or anything like that but

00:19:05.800 --> 00:19:09.480
[Guest]: I I get your question that a lot of people when they are in campus politics

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:13.520
[Guest]: they want change like a lot of my friends in college they were part of

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:17.480
[Guest]: campus politics because they felt as strongly as me and you know when I when

00:19:17.480 --> 00:19:20.600
[Guest]: I use the word violently I mean that there are a lot of people who want

00:19:20.600 --> 00:19:24.440
[Guest]: change but they don't do anything or they are unable to do something because

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:29.080
[Guest]: to be in that particular campus where everybody is very vocal and you know

00:19:29.080 --> 00:19:32.760
[Guest]: they can even be physically violent you need to have some sort of that that

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:38.200
[Guest]: courage in you or or rather that to be foolish my dad used to think I was

00:19:38.200 --> 00:19:43.560
[Guest]: foolish not just not courageous because I was in trouble all the time and those

00:19:43.560 --> 00:19:48.760
[Guest]: people who are much more spunkier than me or much more dedicated than me in

00:19:48.760 --> 00:19:54.240
[Guest]: college now I see a lot of them have just become your everyday citizens and

00:19:54.240 --> 00:19:58.120
[Guest]: they're not bothered about things that happen around them and I feel that at

00:19:58.120 --> 00:20:02.280
[Guest]: every stage they could have done something at least use a social media

00:20:02.280 --> 00:20:06.160
[Guest]: accounts and nothing else you know to speak about things around them I don't

00:20:06.160 --> 00:20:10.720
[Guest]: know I find it baffling that people can have a certain character while growing

00:20:10.720 --> 00:20:16.840
[Guest]: up and it just disappears that you are very you are citizens who are really

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:20.840
[Guest]: bothered about what happens within your campus itself as students because you

00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:23.720
[Guest]: are invested in that campus right you want things to change you want things to

00:20:23.720 --> 00:20:28.240
[Guest]: happen in a certain way but when you go to a larger canvas which is the the

00:20:28.240 --> 00:20:32.120
[Guest]: world around you your workplace you don't have an opinion anymore that you

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:38.080
[Guest]: are just happy to be part of the flow which does surprise me baffle me but I

00:20:38.080 --> 00:20:43.000
[Guest]: think around eight ten years ago I stopped worrying about it I used to

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:46.720
[Guest]: think that we can we should change people we should make everyone more

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:51.080
[Guest]: reactive but now I think maybe they are all in a safer place everybody doesn't

00:20:51.080 --> 00:20:55.280
[Guest]: have to be reactive in this world people can live in their small happy shells

00:20:55.280 --> 00:20:58.880
[Guest]: like my brother for example he's studying the same college as me just one

00:20:58.880 --> 00:21:02.760
[Guest]: if this part when this podcast comes out he's not going to forgive me for this

00:21:02.760 --> 00:21:07.360
[Guest]: but he's one year younger to me and in college he did not want anybody to know

00:21:07.360 --> 00:21:11.640
[Guest]: that I am his sister because you know he always thought that I would get beaten

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:17.720
[Guest]: up therefore because they can't beat up a girl they may as well as beat up her

00:21:17.720 --> 00:21:21.160
[Guest]: brother so you don't want anyone to know that we are siblings because he will and

00:21:21.160 --> 00:21:26.280
[Guest]: he will run after college he will not stay back but he who did not want to

00:21:26.280 --> 00:21:31.320
[Guest]: have any involvement is now a changed person in the sense that he has a he has

00:21:31.320 --> 00:21:35.400
[Guest]: a thought process about what happens he's vocal about it so I've seen both

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:40.080
[Guest]: sides I feel people who are involved in things and then suddenly they don't want

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:44.560
[Guest]: to know anything happening around the world and others who were not like that

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:47.520
[Guest]: but now are more invested in what is happening around them so I think people

00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:51.160
[Guest]: change a lot from what they were in their campus is only very few people

00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:55.200
[Amit Varma]: continue the same way and if your brother is listening to this boss your

00:21:55.200 --> 00:21:58.520
[Amit Varma]: logic was perfectly sound because you know that's what they would do right yeah

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:03.160
[Guest]: I wish he was beaten up once or twice but it never actually happened yeah did

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:07.560
[Amit Varma]: you ever beat up yeah yeah of course and did you ever use your knife or did you

00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:11.320
[Guest]: ever feel like you might use it it was just I mean it's not like we're ever

00:22:11.320 --> 00:22:15.280
[Guest]: going to end up using that knife but we would be told by the seniors that you

00:22:15.280 --> 00:22:18.840
[Guest]: should bring knife in case something happens there is one instance when this

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:24.800
[Guest]: boy was like beaten up and they used a boot and smashed his face so you can

00:22:24.800 --> 00:22:28.920
[Guest]: imagine right in a campus when all this happens is so much of chatter and

00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:35.720
[Guest]: tension and excitement and everything so college life was something like for many

00:22:35.720 --> 00:22:39.040
[Guest]: people they may they may think why just go study and come back what did you

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:42.880
[Guest]: study I actually can't remember what I studied I just know debit what comes in

00:22:42.880 --> 00:22:48.280
[Guest]: and credit what goes out that's all I can remember but rest of who I am that

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:53.000
[Amit Varma]: those five years did shape me yeah I mean I'm kind of amazed you chose commerce

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:56.800
[Amit Varma]: because people either do science or they do arts because they can just chill and

00:22:56.800 --> 00:23:02.840
[Guest]: you know but commerce is just to me seems so boring and it was very

00:23:02.840 --> 00:23:07.720
[Guest]: especially learning for the exam it was so boring I don't even know why people I

00:23:07.720 --> 00:23:11.000
[Guest]: mean I'm sorry to everybody who loves commerce who's listening to this and

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:15.440
[Guest]: also it was a waste for me right I'm not even using the skill of anything that I

00:23:15.440 --> 00:23:19.480
[Guest]: learned I now wish I'd done arts or English but I just didn't want to do

00:23:19.480 --> 00:23:23.360
[Guest]: science and a lot of people I like were already in the commerce stream so I

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:27.080
[Amit Varma]: thought okay let's go join commerce and you know one of the things that strikes

00:23:27.080 --> 00:23:29.760
[Amit Varma]: me about you know what you've been speaking about for the last few minutes

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:34.200
[Amit Varma]: is how different you are from both me and most of my guests who've come on the

00:23:34.200 --> 00:23:39.680
[Amit Varma]: show because in my case of course I was not involved in politics at all but I

00:23:39.680 --> 00:23:44.800
[Amit Varma]: remember that I wasn't fully shaped then in any way I had no clarity about what I

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:49.080
[Amit Varma]: want to do I had vague ideas I will write books I will do this but I was

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:53.280
[Amit Varma]: also struck by what I think is a uniform anxiety especially among the young when

00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:56.600
[Amit Varma]: they start going to college which is the anxiety of what other people think of

00:23:56.600 --> 00:24:00.440
[Amit Varma]: you so you're always trying to project yourself in this way or that way or be

00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:03.840
[Amit Varma]: super cool and you know if I ever carried a knife the only reason I would

00:24:03.840 --> 00:24:07.820
[Amit Varma]: do it is so that I seem cool not because I might have to actually use it the

00:24:07.820 --> 00:24:11.920
[Amit Varma]: horror and it seems that you had way more clarity at least in terms of what

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:15.440
[Amit Varma]: you don't want to do that I don't want to do science or I don't want to go to

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:19.720
[Amit Varma]: these bloody coaching classes you had tremendous clarity and you had a sense

00:24:19.720 --> 00:24:22.800
[Amit Varma]: of what you're doing and I guess even your parents or that when they let you

00:24:22.800 --> 00:24:26.720
[Amit Varma]: stay out till 930 or whatever while your poor brother has to rush back at 620

00:24:26.720 --> 00:24:33.840
[Amit Varma]: let's not define him as poor brother but yes please continue yeah okay yeah so a

00:24:33.840 --> 00:24:37.400
[Amit Varma]: lot of this clarity I can see in terms of what you don't want to do you're very

00:24:37.400 --> 00:24:40.680
[Amit Varma]: clear about what you don't want to do and you don't you won't do that but was

00:24:40.680 --> 00:24:46.200
[Amit Varma]: that anxiety there in other ways and was this clarity also there in terms of what

00:24:46.200 --> 00:24:50.600
[Amit Varma]: am I going to go ahead and do like what was your self-image like like before that

00:24:50.600 --> 00:24:54.960
[Amit Varma]: NDTV moment I guess I was 97 if they were gonna hurt just step down before

00:24:54.960 --> 00:24:59.080
[Amit Varma]: that moment what would have been your sort of conception of where you're going

00:24:59.080 --> 00:25:02.680
[Guest]: and what you want to do and so on and so forth so I've actually never worried

00:25:02.680 --> 00:25:07.600
[Guest]: about what I will become when people used to ask me what will you become I in

00:25:07.600 --> 00:25:10.640
[Guest]: fact I don't even remember anyone really asking me what do you want to become

00:25:10.640 --> 00:25:14.880
[Guest]: people just assumed I'll become a lot of things there was one point of time when

00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:18.480
[Guest]: everybody used to tell me you should become an IAS officer you should become

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:23.080
[Guest]: an IPS officer this is all I would hear go for civil service exam and one point

00:25:23.080 --> 00:25:27.680
[Guest]: of time I thought okay maybe I should do that and I bought my father whenever I

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:31.000
[Guest]: want to become something my father will say okay fine and he went goes and buys

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:35.160
[Guest]: all these readers digest and the Malayala Manorama yearbook and I used to

00:25:35.160 --> 00:25:39.080
[Guest]: read all that and I'm like okay fine this is a decent job where I can also be

00:25:39.080 --> 00:25:41.960
[Guest]: rebellious I feel like okay I am going to make the decision for an entire

00:25:41.960 --> 00:25:46.000
[Guest]: district that's a cool job is what I'm thinking in my head then there is a

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:50.880
[Guest]: collector in Palakkad his name is Ajay Kumar he is now in a very big I think

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:55.920
[Guest]: he's now in a central deployment he was he was in a good posting I don't exactly

00:25:55.920 --> 00:25:59.920
[Guest]: know where he is now he called me to his office because I used to be this

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:03.560
[Guest]: Jawaharlal Nehru and I used to see him all the time for different events so he

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:08.560
[Guest]: knew me and people used to tell him that Oh Danya will become an IAS officer so

00:26:08.560 --> 00:26:11.640
[Guest]: he called me and asked me why do you want to become an IAS officer I said

00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:15.960
[Guest]: because I will change stuff and you know I can do all this so he sat me down and

00:26:15.960 --> 00:26:21.680
[Guest]: said I don't think you are cut out to become an IAS officer because you will

00:26:21.680 --> 00:26:26.720
[Guest]: have to listen to a lot of people including politicians including the

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:30.660
[Guest]: people in the government who may not even know as much as you but you have to

00:26:30.660 --> 00:26:34.760
[Guest]: very carefully think about this it is not a job where you just come and like

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:37.840
[Guest]: an elephant you smash everything and walk I mean these are not exact words he

00:26:37.840 --> 00:26:42.560
[Guest]: used but he basically told me that civil services is something you should be very

00:26:42.560 --> 00:26:47.160
[Guest]: careful about you won't be able to do what you want you are you have to follow

00:26:47.160 --> 00:26:51.320
[Guest]: a lot of other people that's it that one conversation and I decided I am not

00:26:51.320 --> 00:26:55.680
[Guest]: going to become an IAS or IPS officer so that is taken off from my mind right

00:26:55.680 --> 00:26:59.400
[Guest]: because I cannot be in a job where somebody is constantly telling me what I

00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:04.560
[Guest]: should do that is struck from my list then what do I do so have you seen this

00:27:04.560 --> 00:27:10.320
[Guest]: Chitrahaar type programs yeah so Asianet used to have this song program one to

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:15.440
[Guest]: ten top songs during Onam holidays so I used to anchor some of those I mean I

00:27:15.440 --> 00:27:19.080
[Guest]: don't I can't even imagine me doing that like I wear these Pattu Pavada

00:27:19.080 --> 00:27:22.800
[Guest]: clothes and I'll be looking at the camera and saying in really hard Malayalam

00:27:22.800 --> 00:27:26.360
[Guest]: somebody would have written it I will just look at the screen and say that in

00:27:26.360 --> 00:27:31.520
[Guest]: the delay that so I knew I was good on TV and then I saw this NDTV thing and

00:27:31.520 --> 00:27:35.120
[Guest]: I'm like I want to talk on behalf of people so journalism may be my thing

00:27:35.120 --> 00:27:41.320
[Guest]: then I went in search for my for a college so I my father has four sisters

00:27:41.320 --> 00:27:45.760
[Guest]: of which two of them were very involved in my life right from the beginning they

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:50.720
[Guest]: used to buy me books their name Sushila and Vijaya they used to buy me books in

00:27:50.720 --> 00:27:53.760
[Guest]: fact Vijaya used to tell me that you should speak to the mirror like if you

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:57.720
[Guest]: want to speak good English look at the mirror and speak because in Kerala we

00:27:57.720 --> 00:28:01.440
[Guest]: don't converse in English right people speak in Malayalam so she said if you

00:28:01.440 --> 00:28:04.920
[Guest]: want to do good in elocution you have to speak to the mirror so she trained me to

00:28:04.920 --> 00:28:08.840
[Guest]: do that they would both buy me books so they looked up all these colleges and

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:12.440
[Guest]: told me there's an Asian College of Journalism in Chennai I went and applied

00:28:12.440 --> 00:28:16.400
[Guest]: and somehow I got I mean I didn't do well in the entrance by the way in the

00:28:16.400 --> 00:28:20.080
[Guest]: entrance exam I actually did quite badly but they still called me for the

00:28:20.080 --> 00:28:24.120
[Guest]: interview and when they called me for the interview Shashi Kumar sir asked me

00:28:24.120 --> 00:28:28.120
[Guest]: why did you write that wrong that answer and I still couldn't remember the

00:28:28.120 --> 00:28:35.560
[Guest]: correct answer it was a French president's name I forget it now in the 2002

00:28:35.560 --> 00:28:41.360
[Guest]: whatever his name was yes Sarkozy I forgot again now I'm forgetting this so

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:45.880
[Guest]: he told me you didn't know the French president's name I said boss I'm never

00:28:45.880 --> 00:28:49.960
[Guest]: going to report on France right so I didn't think that was important rest

00:28:49.960 --> 00:28:53.920
[Guest]: everything I wrote so why are you I don't know why we should focus on the

00:28:53.920 --> 00:28:59.040
[Guest]: French president then he said he definitely didn't like me I think but I

00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:02.480
[Guest]: reminded him immediately that once upon a time he had given me a prize I won a

00:29:02.480 --> 00:29:06.760
[Guest]: bike once and he had given the prize to me so I said sir do you remember I was

00:29:06.760 --> 00:29:10.960
[Guest]: in that event and you gave me a bike only I think just because I went on

00:29:10.960 --> 00:29:14.640
[Guest]: talking they gave me the admission not because I did well in the entrance exam

00:29:14.640 --> 00:29:18.200
[Guest]: but ACG was also good it was a fun experience learning television all that

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:24.440
[Guest]: so I knew I want to do TV and I won't do journalism but whether I would have become

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:29.160
[Guest]: good at it whether I would have excelled at it I have never worried about it for

00:29:29.160 --> 00:29:33.160
[Guest]: me I'm not a planner like I can't plan the next three months the next six

00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:37.560
[Guest]: months I'm a very daily person even when I run the news minute one of the big

00:29:37.560 --> 00:29:42.120
[Guest]: problems which people in my organization have against me is that I am not a

00:29:42.120 --> 00:29:47.480
[Guest]: planner so now they plan and I'm supposed to follow which is a good thing

00:29:47.480 --> 00:29:51.320
[Guest]: because I don't want to waste my I'm very like even if I my career didn't

00:29:51.320 --> 00:29:53.840
[Guest]: take off or I didn't do well I don't think I would have been very worried I

00:29:53.840 --> 00:29:59.960
[Amit Varma]: would do something else and you know many people sort of stumble into the

00:29:59.960 --> 00:30:02.880
[Amit Varma]: things they do by a mixture of circumstances this happened that

00:30:02.880 --> 00:30:07.600
[Amit Varma]: happened again I got here and it seems to me that even if you kind of took this

00:30:07.600 --> 00:30:12.280
[Amit Varma]: winding road and landed up there you still nevertheless seem totally suited

00:30:12.280 --> 00:30:16.560
[Amit Varma]: for it in the sense that you've got initiative you can speak I'm guessing

00:30:16.560 --> 00:30:20.160
[Amit Varma]: that when it comes to chasing stories and following something you have that

00:30:20.160 --> 00:30:24.560
[Amit Varma]: drive so do you feel that this is the thing that you were suited for that you

00:30:24.560 --> 00:30:29.120
[Amit Varma]: actually fell into something that matched the person that you are I guess

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:33.840
[Guest]: so I mean I can't imagine myself doing some other job I would be very bored if

00:30:33.840 --> 00:30:38.200
[Guest]: I was doing any other job because more than anything else I interact with so

00:30:38.200 --> 00:30:44.800
[Guest]: many people I don't understand where if I was in a office cabin and I had to

00:30:44.800 --> 00:30:49.520
[Guest]: look at the look at doc I'm sure I'm doing work which changes the world but

00:30:49.520 --> 00:30:52.640
[Guest]: for me it's important that I meet different kind of people that I

00:30:52.640 --> 00:30:56.960
[Guest]: interact with different kind of people if not then then it just stifles me I

00:30:56.960 --> 00:31:01.680
[Guest]: don't know I feel there's no purpose therefore yes this job very well does

00:31:01.680 --> 00:31:06.520
[Guest]: suit me if I didn't do this maybe I would be in TV in some other way maybe I

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:09.800
[Guest]: would have been filmmaking but I'm not very artistic therefore I would have

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:14.280
[Guest]: sucked at it I mean I would be there in some position or the other I don't know

00:31:14.280 --> 00:31:19.160
[Amit Varma]: what you just said about meeting people is also very interesting because another

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:24.080
[Amit Varma]: of the themes that I keep addressing on my show is about sort of the difference

00:31:24.080 --> 00:31:28.480
[Amit Varma]: between the abstract and the concrete that you know abstract notions like

00:31:28.480 --> 00:31:32.240
[Amit Varma]: nationalism and purity and blah blah blah and their notions that really divide

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:36.080
[Amit Varma]: us and a lot of the negativity comes from there and it's really easy on to sit

00:31:36.080 --> 00:31:39.920
[Amit Varma]: on Twitter and be just completely toxic and it's all abstract but when you go

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:43.480
[Amit Varma]: out and actually meet people you know you then those abstractions go away

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:46.400
[Amit Varma]: because you're encountering people in the concrete you you know you're

00:31:46.400 --> 00:31:49.240
[Amit Varma]: actually meeting people from all kinds of different backgrounds and you're

00:31:49.240 --> 00:31:54.320
[Amit Varma]: making friends and all of that so it becomes kind of hard to carry that

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:58.120
[Amit Varma]: toxicity everywhere and I think one thing that we've been doing kind of more

00:31:58.120 --> 00:32:02.720
[Amit Varma]: and more in in this digital age which I think is a massive net positive in terms

00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:05.600
[Amit Varma]: of how technology has empowered individuals and people like you and me

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:09.360
[Amit Varma]: as well but one sort of negative drawback of that is that we're not we

00:32:09.360 --> 00:32:13.000
[Amit Varma]: don't engage enough with real people we don't actually sit down and have real

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.560
[Amit Varma]: conversations with them anymore where we are you know we're just chilling with

00:32:16.560 --> 00:32:21.160
[Amit Varma]: them there's no agenda there's nothing functional to do those quiet moments

00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:25.640
[Amit Varma]: have gone out of our life and so on and so forth and you are out among the

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:30.600
[Amit Varma]: people all the time and while it's hard to you know pinpoint if that is a factor

00:32:30.600 --> 00:32:34.360
[Amit Varma]: or whatever do you feel that that that sets you apart from other people who

00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:37.840
[Amit Varma]: maybe don't do that there are so many ivory tower opinion writers will be

00:32:37.840 --> 00:32:41.280
[Amit Varma]: sitting in their you know living room somewhere writing opinion pieces about

00:32:41.280 --> 00:32:44.720
[Amit Varma]: something that's happening somewhere but they've never actually been there while

00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:48.440
[Amit Varma]: your whole scene is that I'm gonna go there I'm gonna talk to people I'm going

00:32:48.440 --> 00:32:52.880
[Amit Varma]: to try to kind of understand that so you know is that something that you see

00:32:52.880 --> 00:32:56.280
[Amit Varma]: around you quite apart from the fact that you like to meet people but that

00:32:56.280 --> 00:33:00.200
[Amit Varma]: meeting people is good it changes you it makes you different of course I mean I

00:33:00.200 --> 00:33:03.440
[Guest]: don't look down upon people who write opinions they are welcoming they're

00:33:03.440 --> 00:33:07.200
[Guest]: welcome to write their opinions but I feel people should not think that that

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:11.960
[Guest]: opinion is what really matters or that is what is happening on the ground I

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:16.200
[Guest]: feel those who write opinion pieces should understand that perhaps what they

00:33:16.200 --> 00:33:19.160
[Guest]: write is not reflective of what is happening on the ground it's but it's

00:33:19.160 --> 00:33:24.400
[Guest]: just what they think what they feel I differentiate myself from that like

00:33:24.400 --> 00:33:30.400
[Guest]: today morning there is a story of a rape survivor she's alleged rape in a college

00:33:30.400 --> 00:33:35.520
[Guest]: I have a reporter who's doing the story but I I still would message that

00:33:35.520 --> 00:33:39.480
[Guest]: survivor to just say that look we are here as we are here if you need anything

00:33:39.480 --> 00:33:45.960
[Guest]: you can support us so for me that human communication is very very important if

00:33:45.960 --> 00:33:49.160
[Guest]: it's a story even if we are going to tell somebody's story not tell someone's

00:33:49.160 --> 00:33:52.680
[Guest]: story to interact with different kinds of people because everybody's problem is

00:33:52.680 --> 00:33:56.520
[Guest]: not the same like even if when you talk about people who are angry on Twitter

00:33:56.520 --> 00:34:00.040
[Guest]: and who talk about communalism and bigotry and all that you walk into a

00:34:00.040 --> 00:34:02.920
[Guest]: street where there are let's say a lot of Muslims living and you have seen a

00:34:02.920 --> 00:34:07.720
[Guest]: riot a few days ago they're not going to be reacting the exact same way that you

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:11.720
[Guest]: want them to react they have different concerns in life they want their

00:34:11.720 --> 00:34:15.280
[Guest]: children to go to school safely the next day they want their shop to open for

00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:19.400
[Guest]: them it's not about immediately defeating someone in the next election

00:34:19.400 --> 00:34:24.040
[Guest]: right which may be what you are thinking that's their immediate agenda that's not

00:34:24.040 --> 00:34:28.520
[Guest]: their immediate agenda is just getting back to their lives so everywhere you go

00:34:28.520 --> 00:34:33.560
[Guest]: and you meet people you understand that their needs what they want is very

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:37.360
[Guest]: different from what you think they want even the hijab story which we have been

00:34:37.360 --> 00:34:41.360
[Guest]: covering for so many weeks there are so many people who write to us even from

00:34:41.360 --> 00:34:46.040
[Guest]: the Muslim community itself saying that we are against this we are for this so

00:34:46.040 --> 00:34:49.600
[Guest]: there are so many opinions right so how do you condense all that opinion to

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:53.920
[Guest]: write into an into an opinion piece I think I'm not I I'm not someone who

00:34:53.920 --> 00:34:57.400
[Guest]: cannot do that like I said in the beginning cut the clutter it's not my

00:34:57.400 --> 00:35:04.400
[Guest]: it's not my game because first I feel that it's too much onus on one human

00:35:04.400 --> 00:35:09.720
[Guest]: being to just have an opinion about everything under the Sun and the second

00:35:09.720 --> 00:35:13.200
[Guest]: is if I'm going to give my opinion I have also I also have to be open to

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:19.520
[Guest]: criticism and that's like another whole cycle of anger and outrage and people

00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:22.740
[Guest]: are like why did you say this why did you not say that I would rather not do

00:35:22.740 --> 00:35:27.440
[Guest]: it just do ground reporting help my reporters and that's about it but I

00:35:27.440 --> 00:35:35.200
[Guest]: think in India we have to understand that 15 years ago if we just had news

00:35:35.200 --> 00:35:38.800
[Guest]: which is looking at side A side B side C and putting it out together we cannot

00:35:38.800 --> 00:35:44.520
[Guest]: afford to do that anymore if side A is right side B is toxic then you have to

00:35:44.520 --> 00:35:50.040
[Guest]: call side B right so the way we report has changed and for that also you need

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:54.280
[Guest]: to interact with people more see the pandemic has changed journalism quite a

00:35:54.280 --> 00:35:58.000
[Guest]: bit in India and two years is a long time a lot of people who are joining

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:01.960
[Guest]: organizations now are not stepping out of their houses they are sitting

00:36:01.960 --> 00:36:05.520
[Guest]: somewhere they're making phone calls and they're talking to people there is only

00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:10.080
[Guest]: this much that a person will tell you if you call them over a phone call if they

00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:13.640
[Guest]: know you they've heard of you maybe they will open up but it's still not

00:36:13.640 --> 00:36:17.080
[Guest]: comparable to you actually going and meeting them and understanding them

00:36:17.080 --> 00:36:20.560
[Guest]: maybe you will not use most of it for your story but it's very important for

00:36:20.560 --> 00:36:25.000
[Guest]: you as a journalist to understand perspectives so that way for me when you

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:29.640
[Guest]: talk about abstract and concrete abstract never works but that's just me

00:36:29.640 --> 00:36:34.320
[Guest]: I said I can only process daily stuff but for many others maybe like I have

00:36:34.320 --> 00:36:37.680
[Guest]: people in my team who can actually understand something happening on the

00:36:37.680 --> 00:36:41.120
[Guest]: ground and they can write strong opinion pieces that's fine it's their job they

00:36:41.120 --> 00:36:46.320
[Guest]: can write it but the person who reads it also should should know that this is not

00:36:46.320 --> 00:36:50.640
[Guest]: the only one opinion that matters read more understand more you know I think

00:36:50.640 --> 00:36:55.360
[Amit Varma]: just thinking aloud you know if cut the clutter is kind of one kind of thing

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:59.280
[Amit Varma]: that you need you also need that but there is also embrace the clutter which

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:03.520
[Amit Varma]: seems to be more what reporters need to do that actually go out there and engage

00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:08.120
[Amit Varma]: with the complexity of the world and I think even people who do opinion pieces

00:37:08.120 --> 00:37:11.400
[Amit Varma]: I have written a fair bit of opinion in my time at least have to have the

00:37:11.400 --> 00:37:15.280
[Amit Varma]: humility to realize that there is a real world out there you always have to be

00:37:15.280 --> 00:37:20.640
[Amit Varma]: open to kind of engaging with it like Abhinandan when we did our episode

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:24.240
[Amit Varma]: together he told me this interesting story of something he realized when he

00:37:24.240 --> 00:37:27.600
[Amit Varma]: was in the Northeast where they went to this village which was pretty remote and

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:30.240
[Amit Varma]: they asked the people that what do you want the government to do for you and

00:37:30.240 --> 00:37:34.760
[Amit Varma]: those guys said we want them to build a cinema hall so that's what I said yeah

00:37:34.760 --> 00:37:38.400
[Amit Varma]: and I've been and the logic is fantastic because Abhinandan and gang are like

00:37:38.400 --> 00:37:41.840
[Amit Varma]: really surprised and they're like but you know you would want roads you

00:37:41.840 --> 00:37:45.680
[Amit Varma]: wouldn't want it things with positive externalities more toilets and these

00:37:45.680 --> 00:37:49.840
[Amit Varma]: guys are no we need entertainment in our lives we go to nearby cities for that

00:37:49.840 --> 00:37:54.160
[Amit Varma]: people die in car accidents that death rate is high just give us something in

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:57.480
[Amit Varma]: the village and that's something somebody who embraces the clutter a

00:37:57.480 --> 00:38:01.040
[Amit Varma]: reporter like you will find that out but somebody sitting in Delhi and doing an

00:38:01.040 --> 00:38:05.320
[Guest]: opinion piece will have absolutely no idea so Amit I'm saying the people who

00:38:05.320 --> 00:38:08.920
[Guest]: write opinion pieces I like I said I don't look down upon their work at all

00:38:08.920 --> 00:38:14.440
[Guest]: yeah I watch I watch cut the clutter all the time but my point is I am NOT

00:38:14.440 --> 00:38:18.920
[Guest]: suited for that job and yes the problem with what Abhinandan said is that

00:38:18.920 --> 00:38:23.640
[Guest]: nowadays if if a reporter is being sent to to the Northeast and the village says

00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:29.640
[Guest]: that I want a cinema hall and I'm not bothered about your positive developments

00:38:29.640 --> 00:38:33.480
[Guest]: or voting for or against a party and the reporter says look boss in that village

00:38:33.480 --> 00:38:37.000
[Guest]: they want a cinema hall that's the biggest problem the editor may say no

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:41.520
[Guest]: but I want those three quotes from you where they are saying that I am against

00:38:41.520 --> 00:38:45.360
[Guest]: the BJP for the BJP I'm for the Congress I'm against the Congress so this is

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:50.920
[Guest]: another problem which we are imposing on people who work with us and I also have

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:54.120
[Guest]: done that I'm not saying I haven't there are many times reporters have gone to

00:38:54.120 --> 00:38:57.040
[Guest]: the field found something else and I'd be like no you have to find the other

00:38:57.040 --> 00:39:00.840
[Guest]: thing because in my mind I've made made that up right I've made that angle in my

00:39:00.840 --> 00:39:04.720
[Guest]: mind and I have also figured out the headline so I want a story constructed

00:39:04.720 --> 00:39:09.400
[Guest]: around it but I do actively tell myself that that's not how it is you have been

00:39:09.400 --> 00:39:13.040
[Guest]: a ground reporter you cannot be imposing your thoughts on a ground reporter so

00:39:13.040 --> 00:39:16.560
[Guest]: that's a reminder I give myself all the time but I think when we become very

00:39:16.560 --> 00:39:21.160
[Guest]: desk driven when the desk takes a lot of calls and the reporter see something

00:39:21.160 --> 00:39:26.480
[Guest]: very different on the ground we still want them to write according to our

00:39:26.480 --> 00:39:31.520
[Guest]: sensibilities that's something we all have to stop whether it's the hijab

00:39:31.520 --> 00:39:35.680
[Guest]: issue whatever issue you're covering the Sabarimala issue you you have made up

00:39:35.680 --> 00:39:39.760
[Guest]: your mind right we should not we should stop doing that and I as I read more

00:39:39.760 --> 00:39:44.440
[Guest]: stories I feel like reporters are also trying to fill in that image which that

00:39:44.440 --> 00:39:49.320
[Guest]: organization has or sometimes they don't even tell you the reality like they feel

00:39:49.320 --> 00:39:52.160
[Guest]: something has happened on the ground which is not exactly correct it's

00:39:52.160 --> 00:39:55.960
[Guest]: questionable but they feel they have to write in a certain way that's only then

00:39:55.960 --> 00:40:01.720
[Guest]: the audience will appreciate them or that echo chamber will feel happy that they have been

00:40:01.720 --> 00:40:06.880
[Guest]: validated so we all have to move out of those of those echo chambers you know

00:40:06.880 --> 00:40:10.240
[Amit Varma]: take me through more of your sort of journalism journey you're at ACJ and

00:40:10.240 --> 00:40:16.880
[Amit Varma]: you've kind of done journalism and I'm curious also about how people form their

00:40:16.880 --> 00:40:20.840
[Amit Varma]: conceptions about what journalism is because I kind of grew up in the 80s

00:40:20.840 --> 00:40:24.920
[Amit Varma]: started working in the mid 90s I'm probably three or four years older than

00:40:24.920 --> 00:40:29.040
[Amit Varma]: you I'm guessing everyone who kind of got into journalism then I mean I didn't

00:40:29.040 --> 00:40:34.200
[Amit Varma]: but many of my peers did that was just the age before journalism schools right

00:40:34.200 --> 00:40:38.320
[Amit Varma]: that is also the age before the internet so you're not exposed to global

00:40:38.320 --> 00:40:42.640
[Amit Varma]: journalism you're not not exposed to books on journalism you're not exposed

00:40:42.640 --> 00:40:47.200
[Amit Varma]: to different views of how journalism should be conducted and there's no one

00:40:47.200 --> 00:40:51.800
[Amit Varma]: training you so you're pretty much learning on the job and many of India's

00:40:51.800 --> 00:40:56.440
[Amit Varma]: media houses at the time if not all don't really have any kind of induction

00:40:56.440 --> 00:40:59.960
[Amit Varma]: scene going on where you're taught the values of the game you're taught the

00:40:59.960 --> 00:41:05.640
[Amit Varma]: craft in a systematic way none of that really happens which is why for a lot of

00:41:05.640 --> 00:41:10.040
[Amit Varma]: people it becomes like a functional thing you're not getting meta and

00:41:10.040 --> 00:41:13.880
[Amit Varma]: thinking about it one step ahead in terms of what are my values what am I

00:41:13.880 --> 00:41:18.040
[Amit Varma]: really trying to do what does a journalist do you know and all of those

00:41:18.040 --> 00:41:24.480
[Amit Varma]: things so what was that process for you like of forming a view or what is this

00:41:24.480 --> 00:41:27.920
[Amit Varma]: thing called journalism because initially when we notice journalism we

00:41:27.920 --> 00:41:31.640
[Amit Varma]: notice oh there's an article in a page and someone went out and reported or oh

00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:35.360
[Amit Varma]: there's this TV show happening and an anchor is cutting to a reporter and the

00:41:35.360 --> 00:41:39.000
[Amit Varma]: reporter has spoken to two people and that's a bare bones of it but there's

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:42.600
[Amit Varma]: obviously so much else behind that including that whole value system so how

00:41:42.600 --> 00:41:49.680
[Amit Varma]: did your thinking about journalism kind of evolve through the years so from the

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:54.080
[Guest]: first part of my story you must have thought that I am very clear on what I

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:58.680
[Guest]: want to do etc okay then I end up in this journalism school I pass out and I

00:41:58.680 --> 00:42:01.760
[Guest]: freaking have no clue what to do after this because I don't know how to be a

00:42:01.760 --> 00:42:06.560
[Guest]: journalist it's very cool to think I am a journalist and I've got a job so my

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:10.200
[Guest]: first job was with this Malayalam channel called India vision it was

00:42:10.200 --> 00:42:14.960
[Guest]: actually the first 24-hour news channel that Kerala got and Shashi Kumar was a

00:42:14.960 --> 00:42:19.280
[Guest]: part of the channel so he made a few of us join it three or four of us and they

00:42:19.280 --> 00:42:23.280
[Guest]: told me you go to the Delhi Bureau and I am in charge of the Delhi Bureau for a

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:28.560
[Guest]: new channel and along with me is one woman camera person and another reporter

00:42:28.560 --> 00:42:31.760
[Guest]: who is a student in Jamia and that's it I'm supposed to look after the Delhi

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:35.560
[Guest]: Bureau of the channel and I have no freaking clue about Delhi I don't know

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:39.320
[Guest]: anything I just land up in Delhi and they've given us a house and said this

00:42:39.320 --> 00:42:42.320
[Guest]: is your office come house you do whatever you want we're staying there

00:42:42.320 --> 00:42:47.880
[Guest]: we're working there my first story I will never forget it was a it was a

00:42:47.880 --> 00:42:53.040
[Guest]: nurse who got raped she was a Malayali nurse and in that hospital the ward boy

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:58.880
[Guest]: had raped her and he gouged the eye out he took her eye out like it was falling

00:42:58.880 --> 00:43:02.800
[Guest]: when she woke up in the morning after the rape she realized that her eye was

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:07.200
[Guest]: just like falling off and they had to remove it so it was a first story I I

00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:12.360
[Guest]: reached the hospital and all the Malayali reporters realized I am this Malayali

00:43:12.360 --> 00:43:17.760
[Guest]: woman journalist and they were all too I mean you know as a man sometimes it's

00:43:17.760 --> 00:43:21.080
[Guest]: difficult to speak to survivors or survivors families so they sent me

00:43:21.080 --> 00:43:26.480
[Guest]: inside to talk to the victim and the family that was my first story but after

00:43:26.480 --> 00:43:30.600
[Guest]: that I never I mean I kept in touch with that story for a long time this is a

00:43:30.600 --> 00:43:33.960
[Guest]: very famous case where it went to the court and the court said why don't you

00:43:33.960 --> 00:43:38.200
[Guest]: marry this guy and the woman just lost in the court and asked the judge why why

00:43:38.200 --> 00:43:42.520
[Guest]: should I marry him but I have not been able to find her I've been looking for

00:43:42.520 --> 00:43:46.560
[Guest]: her for many years but I've never been able to find her after that now this was

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:51.560
[Guest]: my first story but my later career in in India vision in Delhi was not at all

00:43:51.560 --> 00:43:56.120
[Guest]: like this because in Delhi it was set to work I mean I can't remember the timings

00:43:56.120 --> 00:43:59.880
[Guest]: but 2 p.m. you go to CPM office 3 p.m. you go to BJP office 4 p.m. you go to

00:43:59.880 --> 00:44:03.760
[Guest]: Congress office you cover all their press meets come back and you cut your

00:44:03.760 --> 00:44:09.000
[Guest]: packages CPM said this and so I knew lunch I will eat in BJP office evening

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:13.000
[Guest]: snack I will get in very less salary right so evening snack I will get in

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:16.640
[Guest]: Congress office and my life went on like that I had nothing much to do if some

00:44:16.640 --> 00:44:20.680
[Guest]: big crime happens or I mean what would a Kerala audience do with a crime in Delhi

00:44:20.680 --> 00:44:24.840
[Guest]: but if something important happens I would be sent I went to Rajasthan to

00:44:24.840 --> 00:44:30.840
[Guest]: cover elections I have no clue what I'm doing I interviewed so many politicians

00:44:30.840 --> 00:44:33.640
[Guest]: without understanding the basics because I'm not reading anything I'm not

00:44:33.640 --> 00:44:37.240
[Guest]: watching anything I'm just being sent to places saying go interview people and I

00:44:37.240 --> 00:44:40.640
[Guest]: will just trust my mic and ask three nonsensical questions and they will

00:44:40.640 --> 00:44:45.200
[Guest]: answer I'm like yeah I got my exclusive that's it and by the end of my stay in

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:49.640
[Guest]: Delhi it was a 2004 elections and I still remember watching Anubhav Bosley

00:44:49.640 --> 00:44:55.240
[Guest]: Nidhi Rasdan, Pallavi Ghosh and all outside the various offices I will never

00:44:55.240 --> 00:44:59.120
[Guest]: forget there was this one meeting the NCP and the Congress decide to come

00:44:59.120 --> 00:45:05.000
[Guest]: together so Sharath Pawar and Sonia Gandhi and everybody's in the meeting

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:08.760
[Guest]: and I have no clue what is happening I'm just waiting for the press meet because

00:45:08.760 --> 00:45:11.960
[Guest]: when the press meet happens I will know right but I'm getting calls from my

00:45:11.960 --> 00:45:16.960
[Guest]: channel saying NDTV is breaking that Sharath Pawar and Sonia Gandhi or whatever

00:45:16.960 --> 00:45:21.120
[Guest]: they have decided to come together I don't know how the press meet is going

00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:25.800
[Guest]: has not started even then I don't know how to build a source eight months I've

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:29.400
[Guest]: been there I don't have a single source in the NCP or the Congress people sitting

00:45:29.400 --> 00:45:32.680
[Guest]: next to me have got their seniors they've got sources and they've been

00:45:32.680 --> 00:45:36.840
[Guest]: they're getting SMS from inside the meeting and I'm like that's how you

00:45:36.840 --> 00:45:41.040
[Guest]: build source it's not enough that you cover a press meet anyway I got tired of

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:44.880
[Guest]: the entire Delhi business because you can't do anything in Delhi you just have

00:45:44.880 --> 00:45:49.320
[Guest]: to go like a cow herd the cow herd goes to BJP office all everybody goes there

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:53.280
[Guest]: together I mean it was just too irritating too robotic so I said I'm

00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:57.760
[Guest]: that's a screw Delhi I'm gonna go away from Delhi and I went to Chennai and I

00:45:57.760 --> 00:46:01.280
[Guest]: didn't have a job and I had my loan to pay so I definitely had to get a job

00:46:01.280 --> 00:46:05.600
[Guest]: immediately I walked in New Indian Express office and I said I need a job

00:46:05.600 --> 00:46:09.880
[Guest]: they said we don't have vacancy now I said no but I really need you look at my

00:46:09.880 --> 00:46:13.560
[Guest]: resume I worked in Delhi and actually they were quite nice they gave me a job

00:46:13.560 --> 00:46:17.840
[Guest]: they said okay join next week and I joined the New Indian Express and first

00:46:17.840 --> 00:46:22.880
[Guest]: they put me in the features team I was so bad at it so bad at it that the

00:46:22.880 --> 00:46:28.400
[Guest]: features team head his name is Joy he went and told the reporting team that

00:46:28.400 --> 00:46:31.800
[Guest]: after one or two weeks he said you take her on reporting she may be good in

00:46:31.800 --> 00:46:35.040
[Guest]: reporting then I went to the reporting team again no sources I don't know what

00:46:35.040 --> 00:46:43.320
[Guest]: to do and TN Gopalan was the head of reporting and D Suresh Kumar Jairaj lot

00:46:43.320 --> 00:46:47.080
[Guest]: of good journalists in Tamil Nadu TN Gopalan also threatened me saying that

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:51.520
[Guest]: you don't know anything I'll take you back into features with features is

00:46:51.520 --> 00:46:55.600
[Guest]: actually a very good department to be in but those times we used to think that oh

00:46:55.600 --> 00:46:58.960
[Guest]: my god writing about pop culture no I just want to be where Jayalalitha and

00:46:58.960 --> 00:47:02.800
[Guest]: Karnanidhi are and all that I said sir give me one chance I will do it so he

00:47:02.800 --> 00:47:07.480
[Guest]: said okay you go to the assembly and I went with this with another senior

00:47:07.480 --> 00:47:10.640
[Guest]: reporter I went to the assembly with him and Jayalalitha is a chief minister then

00:47:10.640 --> 00:47:14.280
[Guest]: so I'm sitting in the assembly and I can't stop talking I'm so excited that

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:19.600
[Guest]: Jayalalitha is there and you know this assembly is going on so I'm like person

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:22.800
[Guest]: sitting next to me I'm continuously whispering and then Jayalalitha just

00:47:22.800 --> 00:47:26.160
[Guest]: looks sideways and then she can see me speak talking and continuously I'm

00:47:26.160 --> 00:47:31.560
[Guest]: talking then after sometime she writes a chit and I don't know anything so I'm

00:47:31.560 --> 00:47:35.280
[Guest]: just sitting quietly I go back to office and I'm called by the resident editor

00:47:35.280 --> 00:47:38.520
[Guest]: into the office and bureau chief and everybody's standing and they said

00:47:38.520 --> 00:47:43.000
[Guest]: Jayalalitha asked who is that girl who's talking so much in the assembly you

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:47.720
[Guest]: cannot go back to the assembly my assembly coverage was cut and I was put

00:47:47.720 --> 00:47:51.200
[Guest]: back into health group I was first a crime reporter two days I survived I

00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:56.320
[Guest]: went to the commissioner's office and I was so put off by you know all these

00:47:56.320 --> 00:47:59.520
[Guest]: crime reporters sitting there and they're just taking down notes and I'm

00:47:59.520 --> 00:48:01.840
[Guest]: like I don't want to do this so I went and told him I don't want to do this I'll do

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:06.320
[Guest]: health reporting and I was clueless in that also for a long time but there's

00:48:06.320 --> 00:48:10.880
[Guest]: this person called Pushpa Narayan she's a health editor of Times of India now

00:48:10.880 --> 00:48:14.880
[Guest]: she was getting transferred to Bangalore she sat down with me and she

00:48:14.880 --> 00:48:20.560
[Guest]: taught me how to write how to write a lead how to make a source like you said

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:25.360
[Guest]: the organization did not have time both the organizations never had any time just

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:29.160
[Guest]: because okay I was like I have interviewed Gehlot in Rajasthan and I

00:48:29.160 --> 00:48:33.320
[Guest]: was only only one Malayalam reporter who got it not just not because I knew

00:48:33.320 --> 00:48:37.000
[Guest]: anything about Gehlot or Rajasthan politics I was just I could push my way

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:41.440
[Guest]: through and get anybody's interview that was my only skill till then but Pushpa

00:48:41.440 --> 00:48:44.120
[Guest]: told me this is not how you do it it's not enough that you're just a pushy

00:48:44.120 --> 00:48:48.440
[Guest]: person you have to get your story and she taught me how to write a story how

00:48:48.440 --> 00:48:51.920
[Guest]: to get a source and many other journalists did but by then I got tired

00:48:51.920 --> 00:48:56.160
[Guest]: of print also I'm like this is not my cup of tea I have to go back to TV and

00:48:56.160 --> 00:49:02.720
[Amit Varma]: that's how I ended up joining Times Now. Wonderful so we have finally reached the

00:49:02.720 --> 00:49:08.280
[Amit Varma]: point where you are Arnab's colleague so what was Times Now like like did you

00:49:08.280 --> 00:49:12.320
[Amit Varma]: have a clearer idea of what do you want to do there what kind of stories do you

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:16.520
[Amit Varma]: want to cover did you have a better idea of that once you're there? See I had made

00:49:16.520 --> 00:49:20.960
[Guest]: up my mind that I will join IBM because Rajdeep Sardesai is someone I really

00:49:20.960 --> 00:49:25.600
[Guest]: wanted to work with and when I left this India version I messaged him he said I

00:49:25.600 --> 00:49:30.480
[Guest]: have also left NDTV so sorry you have to ask NDTV then when I left

00:49:30.480 --> 00:49:33.840
[Guest]: Internet Express he said I mean he doesn't know me or anything but he just

00:49:33.840 --> 00:49:38.000
[Guest]: would reply to messages very politely then I'm like I made up my mind I am

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:42.400
[Guest]: joining Rajdeep Sardesai's Chennai team because he has got he's starting a new channel

00:49:42.400 --> 00:49:47.120
[Guest]: so I've got an interview with Arnab Goswami on Monday the very next day I

00:49:47.120 --> 00:49:51.520
[Guest]: have an interview in Delhi with Rajdeep Sardesai so that's it I'm like I have to

00:49:51.520 --> 00:49:54.080
[Guest]: go for the Times Now interview because somebody has set it up for me I'll go

00:49:54.080 --> 00:49:58.120
[Guest]: there I they'll offer me a job I'm very sure I mean I'm like that okay I'm never

00:49:58.120 --> 00:50:02.480
[Guest]: thinking I'll not get a job I'll say no and I'll go to IBM and there I will get

00:50:02.480 --> 00:50:07.360
[Guest]: the job I go for this interview and I'm I did not expect I did not know much

00:50:07.360 --> 00:50:10.880
[Guest]: about Arnab Goswami except that I've seen him on TV but I didn't realize what

00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:16.040
[Guest]: a forceful personality he is so he asked me do you know Tamil I said yes I mean I

00:50:16.040 --> 00:50:20.160
[Guest]: didn't know Tamil and I mean I was pretty sure if he's going to make me

00:50:20.160 --> 00:50:24.360
[Guest]: read something in Tamil I can make up and he anyway can't read Tamil right so

00:50:24.360 --> 00:50:28.720
[Guest]: and then he gave me the job immediately and he said you have to join from

00:50:28.720 --> 00:50:32.600
[Guest]: tomorrow I said but sir I can't join I don't even have clothes I've just come

00:50:32.600 --> 00:50:36.520
[Guest]: for one day he said no I'll give you an allowance of 10,000 rupees you please go

00:50:36.520 --> 00:50:39.400
[Guest]: buy clothes you have to stay here for one month your training will start from

00:50:39.400 --> 00:50:43.600
[Guest]: tomorrow I'm like I don't know if I should he said no that's it you're just

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:48.720
[Guest]: joining and he was so forceful I did not know how to say no and he they gave me

00:50:48.720 --> 00:50:53.160
[Guest]: the money I went and bought clothes that's it I joined Times Now that's how

00:50:53.160 --> 00:50:58.080
[Guest]: my career in Times Now starts initially you know in TV when you're the junior

00:50:58.080 --> 00:51:03.680
[Guest]: reporter in a bureau they'll make you do all kinds of rubbish Arnab shows the

00:51:03.680 --> 00:51:07.680
[Guest]: night get two vox pops is my job so Arnab is doing some show I'm just on the

00:51:07.680 --> 00:51:13.000
[Guest]: road asking people for opinions or Arnab is doing this one big story so you go

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:16.440
[Guest]: get five or not even Arnab it'll be somebody else in the organization they

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:20.280
[Guest]: are doing some big story in Delhi some politics is happening so you go get two

00:51:20.280 --> 00:51:25.120
[Guest]: or three politicians so at that point of time there were very few TV reporters

00:51:25.120 --> 00:51:31.160
[Guest]: there was NDTV then IBM started then us and headlines today so imagine I come

00:51:31.160 --> 00:51:35.440
[Guest]: from a time when the other reporters would not even share numbers of

00:51:35.440 --> 00:51:39.400
[Guest]: politicians their Kanimozhi's number Dayanidhi Maran's number people would

00:51:39.400 --> 00:51:44.040
[Guest]: not give me they'll say it's a personal number they don't like to give personal

00:51:44.040 --> 00:51:47.720
[Guest]: numbers to everyone so it was as if it was it is bloody somebody's number give

00:51:47.720 --> 00:51:52.960
[Guest]: it to me they will not give so I realized that I can end my entire life I

00:51:52.960 --> 00:51:57.280
[Guest]: can spend just getting vox pops and accosting a Maran or a Kanimozhi and

00:51:57.280 --> 00:52:02.120
[Guest]: getting their bites without ever knowing them without building a source and I

00:52:02.120 --> 00:52:07.600
[Guest]: realized I have to do something else and I planned it I thought okay I will do

00:52:07.600 --> 00:52:11.200
[Guest]: some investigations because anyway they're not going to let me do politics

00:52:11.200 --> 00:52:15.280
[Guest]: and I don't want to do anything else so I planned a few investigations and it

00:52:15.280 --> 00:52:19.480
[Guest]: actually clicked quite well for times now it became CBI investigation and all

00:52:19.480 --> 00:52:22.960
[Guest]: that stuff so they also started taking me more seriously this happened within

00:52:22.960 --> 00:52:26.280
[Guest]: two or three months but the reason I said this Kanimozhi Dayanidhi Maran thing

00:52:26.280 --> 00:52:31.080
[Guest]: is that that was how journalism was it was very access based you have access to

00:52:31.080 --> 00:52:35.960
[Guest]: a person okay fine you know everything and and people would block access for

00:52:35.960 --> 00:52:39.880
[Guest]: everyone else so one decision I took in the beginning itself is that if I get a

00:52:39.880 --> 00:52:44.100
[Guest]: number I will give it to everybody I mean unless it's a it's a survivor in a

00:52:44.100 --> 00:52:46.840
[Guest]: sexual violence who doesn't want me to give or someone says I don't want my

00:52:46.840 --> 00:52:50.240
[Guest]: number to be given if it's a politician who's supposed to talk to every channel

00:52:50.240 --> 00:52:53.760
[Guest]: they would their number will be there with everyone I mean I wanted to make

00:52:53.760 --> 00:52:57.960
[Guest]: sure the Chennai where I work did not have the same access journalism which

00:52:57.960 --> 00:53:02.440
[Guest]: Delhi followed and Delhi I think still follows it you are you are a good

00:53:02.440 --> 00:53:05.920
[Guest]: journalist if you have access to people and a lot of it is cut off because

00:53:05.920 --> 00:53:08.520
[Guest]: people don't share numbers they will not tell you sources they will not share

00:53:08.520 --> 00:53:12.320
[Guest]: anything which I think is very problematic so anyway that's how times

00:53:12.320 --> 00:53:16.920
[Guest]: now started I did well I did investigations it went off well then

00:53:16.920 --> 00:53:21.160
[Guest]: thankfully my bureau chief left the bureau and I was made the bureau chief I

00:53:21.160 --> 00:53:26.800
[Guest]: grew along with the channel and soon I was shifted to Bangalore where I was

00:53:26.800 --> 00:53:30.600
[Guest]: made in charge of all the four southern bureaus there was no Telangana at that

00:53:30.600 --> 00:53:33.840
[Guest]: time it was just unified Andhra Pradesh so I was in charge of all the four

00:53:33.840 --> 00:53:39.400
[Guest]: bureaus it was a good experience and it was a bad experience but by the end of

00:53:39.400 --> 00:53:45.560
[Guest]: eight years I worked eight years in times now I was done with TV so why was

00:53:45.560 --> 00:53:50.400
[Amit Varma]: it a good experience and why was it a bad experience you really want me to

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:54.840
[Guest]: talk about times now in detail and all numbers no I mean it's you right we're

00:53:54.840 --> 00:53:58.840
[Guest]: talking about you so okay so it was a good experience because in the beginning

00:53:58.840 --> 00:54:03.760
[Guest]: here they actually taught me they told me what they want I may not have agreed

00:54:03.760 --> 00:54:06.600
[Guest]: with most of the things they wanted me to do but at least there was a system in

00:54:06.600 --> 00:54:10.040
[Guest]: place where there were a lot of seniors like they are all doing well in

00:54:10.040 --> 00:54:12.960
[Guest]: different different professions Maharukhi Naya, Deepthi, Rahul so many

00:54:12.960 --> 00:54:16.280
[Guest]: people were there they're very indulgent they would tell me Tamanna, Rupali

00:54:16.280 --> 00:54:19.640
[Guest]: lot of seniors in times now they're very indulgent they would help me they

00:54:19.640 --> 00:54:23.000
[Guest]: will tell me get this get this is how you get your elements so it was sorted

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:28.160
[Guest]: for me my bureau chief Vivek he heads news 18 southern channels now so they

00:54:28.160 --> 00:54:33.240
[Guest]: all allowed me to experiment and they were very encouraging that can you

00:54:33.240 --> 00:54:38.780
[Guest]: imagine in times now I have done a one and a half week show on adoptions

00:54:38.780 --> 00:54:42.440
[Guest]: illegal adoptions in India that's something you can't imagine a national

00:54:42.440 --> 00:54:46.320
[Guest]: channel doing anymore but Arnab has sat on news hour and for one and a half

00:54:46.320 --> 00:54:51.240
[Guest]: weeks he's discussed only this illegal adoptions so at that point of time it

00:54:51.240 --> 00:54:56.080
[Guest]: was a platform where if you could bring a story and if you could sell your story

00:54:56.080 --> 00:54:58.920
[Guest]: now it's not enough that you bring a good story you should know how to sell

00:54:58.920 --> 00:55:03.120
[Guest]: it you're like a marketing person the story should be good and you're the way

00:55:03.120 --> 00:55:07.040
[Guest]: you sell it should be so good that Arnab is like this is my so it is always your

00:55:07.040 --> 00:55:11.360
[Guest]: goal is that your story is either in the 8 p.m. show or the 9 p.m. show otherwise

00:55:11.360 --> 00:55:16.720
[Guest]: it's just something which disappears in every bulletin so that way it was good

00:55:16.720 --> 00:55:21.240
[Guest]: there were a chunk of reporters like around 10 or 12 of us who Arnab allowed

00:55:21.240 --> 00:55:27.200
[Guest]: to grow along with the organization and it was a learning process but I think in

00:55:27.200 --> 00:55:32.440
[Guest]: a few years time not only the fact that the newsroom was very toxic that was

00:55:32.440 --> 00:55:35.760
[Guest]: right from the beginning it was toxic but for me personally it was not a

00:55:35.760 --> 00:55:39.440
[Guest]: problem because I was not sitting in Delhi or Bombay I was not inside the

00:55:39.440 --> 00:55:46.160
[Guest]: newsroom right I was far away and I was sort of also it sort of also helped

00:55:46.160 --> 00:55:50.120
[Guest]: because I had some access to Jaya Lalitha now that is an access which I

00:55:50.120 --> 00:55:53.520
[Guest]: can't give to everybody because it's not like I can just pick up my call pick up

00:55:53.520 --> 00:55:57.440
[Guest]: phone and call her but there was some access I had so that also gave me some

00:55:57.440 --> 00:56:02.240
[Guest]: cushioning in times now people knew okay if we can get and Jaya Lalitha's

00:56:02.240 --> 00:56:06.360
[Guest]: interview is very big in TV at that time even even M. Karunanidhi for that matter

00:56:06.360 --> 00:56:10.000
[Guest]: but he was much more democratic that way he would talk to everybody he would come

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:13.800
[Guest]: out and just give bites Jaya Lalitha would never do it but after a point of time I

00:56:13.800 --> 00:56:19.480
[Guest]: realized that the same issue which I described some time back that even if I

00:56:19.480 --> 00:56:23.600
[Guest]: think of a story in a certain way I've gone to the ground and found something

00:56:23.600 --> 00:56:28.360
[Guest]: the channel has decided that this is the story this is the angle I'm taking now

00:56:28.360 --> 00:56:31.720
[Guest]: if my source on the ground is saying no this is not true also it doesn't matter

00:56:31.720 --> 00:56:35.600
[Guest]: to the channel they are still going to do the angle in the other way and this

00:56:35.600 --> 00:56:41.120
[Guest]: became a constant conflict like I've covered scams big national scams like

00:56:41.120 --> 00:56:45.520
[Guest]: the ISRO scam the ISRO Devas scam or so many other things and I realized that

00:56:45.520 --> 00:56:51.200
[Guest]: most of what we are projecting is actually not true but even when I say

00:56:51.200 --> 00:56:55.240
[Guest]: that this is not true boss we shouldn't be doing this we are just making victims

00:56:55.240 --> 00:56:59.200
[Guest]: of people who are actually not done anything wrong nobody would understand

00:56:59.200 --> 00:57:02.680
[Guest]: because the channel has decided this is my headline today the reporter only has

00:57:02.680 --> 00:57:07.800
[Guest]: to fill the gap and soon everybody in the channel started behaving like that

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:12.760
[Guest]: so it just got too much for me beyond a point so one you you have a toxic news

00:57:12.760 --> 00:57:17.800
[Guest]: room second you are just filling the gap of the headline basically they have

00:57:17.800 --> 00:57:23.040
[Guest]: decided this is it and that's that's the angle you take and third is this

00:57:23.040 --> 00:57:27.240
[Guest]: marketing of a story is so much more difficult for a person sitting in South

00:57:27.240 --> 00:57:33.240
[Guest]: India now if I am in Delhi or Bombay even like small pillar falling somewhere

00:57:33.240 --> 00:57:38.080
[Guest]: is a story or Bal Thackeray sneezes it's a story at the same time I tell them

00:57:38.080 --> 00:57:42.400
[Guest]: this is how this big event has happened in Chennai nobody bothers unless it is

00:57:42.400 --> 00:57:47.440
[Guest]: JL Lathore Karunanidhi imagine Karnataka and all they would not cover at all till

00:57:47.440 --> 00:57:51.760
[Guest]: BS Yadurappa and his mining scam came there was hardly any coverage right so

00:57:51.760 --> 00:57:56.560
[Guest]: to market your story continuously like convince people sitting in a Delhi and

00:57:56.560 --> 00:58:02.560
[Guest]: Bombay desk it was it was really hard and when I became the South India Bureau

00:58:02.560 --> 00:58:06.200
[Guest]: chief I'm also responsible for so many others who work with me and they are

00:58:06.200 --> 00:58:10.800
[Guest]: also asking me why is my story not taken I remember the specific instant when my

00:58:10.800 --> 00:58:15.760
[Guest]: colleague Ram he is with me in the news minute now he was very he was 21 years

00:58:15.760 --> 00:58:19.840
[Guest]: old then I think very bubbly very passionate he said I won't do a story on

00:58:19.840 --> 00:58:24.480
[Guest]: Naxals and he's a Tamil Nadu reporter but I still tell Arnab I said boss he

00:58:24.480 --> 00:58:27.480
[Guest]: has some source let him go to Mangalore he wants to do a story from Mangalore on

00:58:27.480 --> 00:58:31.720
[Guest]: the Naxals there he goes there he spends two or three days with the Naxals and he

00:58:31.720 --> 00:58:36.120
[Guest]: comes back and he's got their accounts right so he's got these papers the

00:58:36.120 --> 00:58:40.040
[Guest]: second I saw the paper I knew the story is not going the reason why is because

00:58:40.040 --> 00:58:44.160
[Guest]: the accounts are very simple they are writing grocery some five thousand bucks

00:58:44.160 --> 00:58:49.320
[Guest]: or they're writing some you know chapati dosa or clothes or whatever it's very

00:58:49.320 --> 00:58:54.040
[Guest]: simple accounts that they're maintaining now times now till then has built up this

00:58:54.040 --> 00:58:59.240
[Guest]: great image of Naxals as terrorists we were asked to call Naxals as terrorist

00:58:59.240 --> 00:59:02.760
[Guest]: Naxals and I know people who quit the channel because they disagreed to call

00:59:02.760 --> 00:59:06.840
[Guest]: them terrorist Naxals so the moment Ram brings his story I understand the story

00:59:06.840 --> 00:59:10.520
[Guest]: is not going because it goes against that channels assertion that there is

00:59:10.520 --> 00:59:13.880
[Guest]: Chinese fund there is Pakistani fund they are flush with funds and they have

00:59:13.880 --> 00:59:19.400
[Guest]: ak-47 I mean I'm not contesting that Naxal movements have not got funds from

00:59:19.400 --> 00:59:23.440
[Guest]: other places but a story goes against the grain of what you have argued till

00:59:23.440 --> 00:59:30.160
[Guest]: today the story is rejected this boy is so upset for days how am I going to

00:59:30.160 --> 00:59:33.440
[Guest]: convince him that it's fine move on to your next story right because it's a

00:59:33.440 --> 00:59:37.760
[Guest]: daily job you have to just keep keeping keep on moving so at one point of time

00:59:37.760 --> 00:59:43.040
[Guest]: it got very tiring for me I did not want to do it anymore I specifically remember

00:59:43.040 --> 00:59:46.560
[Guest]: there was violence in the Madras High Court violence to the skillet I had not

00:59:46.560 --> 00:59:51.800
[Guest]: seen till then inside a court there is lathi charge there is stone throwing a

00:59:51.800 --> 00:59:55.480
[Guest]: police station is burnt inside judges are being lathi charged and I'm the

00:59:55.480 --> 00:59:59.920
[Guest]: first television reporter who reached there and my camera person has been hit

00:59:59.920 --> 01:00:04.400
[Guest]: by a stone and I've got really great visuals of you know like hundreds of

01:00:04.400 --> 01:00:07.600
[Guest]: policemen on one side hundreds of lawyers on the other side and they're

01:00:07.600 --> 01:00:12.320
[Guest]: just charging at each other and I'm telling them take the damn visual and

01:00:12.320 --> 01:00:15.880
[Guest]: they're like no something has happened in Bombay I'm like just cut live to me

01:00:15.880 --> 01:00:18.760
[Guest]: then nobody's cutting that finally I called Arnab and said why am I doing

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:22.920
[Guest]: this job it's the biggest visual story then he said see at least he was someone

01:00:22.920 --> 01:00:28.000
[Guest]: who could recognize it so you say okay cut but on a daily basis to argue for a

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:33.120
[Guest]: story like this is very tiring and it's demotivating and I always felt that any

01:00:33.120 --> 01:00:36.720
[Guest]: South Indian story I had to market five times more than somebody sitting in

01:00:36.720 --> 01:00:41.360
[Guest]: Kashmir because time's not a Kashmir obsession and somebody sitting in Delhi

01:00:41.360 --> 01:00:47.120
[Guest]: or Bombay for me the decision to really leave TV came because of Savita

01:00:47.120 --> 01:00:52.360
[Guest]: Harlapana was death in Ireland she was a nurse who hailed from Karnataka and no

01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:55.360
[Guest]: she was I can't remember if she's a nurse but she was from Karnataka and she

01:00:55.360 --> 01:01:00.880
[Guest]: was working in Ireland and she had a very unsafe pregnancy but Ireland would

01:01:00.880 --> 01:01:06.000
[Guest]: not allow abortions and she had to go through the childbirth and she died of

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:10.800
[Guest]: course many many years later Ireland has got a law now which allows abortion only

01:01:10.800 --> 01:01:14.900
[Guest]: because of Savita Harlapana was death and what happened then so we had the

01:01:14.900 --> 01:01:19.680
[Guest]: story with us we are the first people to get Savita Harlapana was you know

01:01:19.680 --> 01:01:24.840
[Guest]: parents in Belgaum and her husband in Ireland I had all my elements ready but

01:01:24.840 --> 01:01:29.760
[Guest]: Bal Thackeray was in hospital and the story wouldn't go and Bal Thackeray didn't

01:01:29.760 --> 01:01:33.040
[Guest]: die the next day the next day and I said see he didn't die he's still in the

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:36.760
[Guest]: hospital why can't you carry the story and they decide to carry the story and

01:01:36.760 --> 01:01:41.640
[Guest]: Bal Thackeray dies and then this whole cycle of Bal Thackeray's funeral

01:01:41.640 --> 01:01:46.280
[Guest]: procession this that and I thought that you know you could have given 20 minutes

01:01:46.280 --> 01:01:52.200
[Guest]: for Savita Harlapana she died and it was an important story to be told you don't

01:01:52.200 --> 01:01:57.320
[Guest]: have to have 24 hours coverage of Bal Thackeray dying is also very important

01:01:57.320 --> 01:02:00.960
[Guest]: I'm not saying it is not but you don't have to dedicate yourself to do only

01:02:00.960 --> 01:02:06.000
[Guest]: that that was the time I decided I cannot do this anymore if I go for a new

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:10.680
[Guest]: job it will be in a place where I don't have to fight for my region I would

01:02:10.680 --> 01:02:13.800
[Guest]: rather join a Tamil channel or a Malayalam news channel at least do my job

01:02:13.800 --> 01:02:18.880
[Guest]: properly I don't have to constantly fight for making my story heard so one

01:02:18.880 --> 01:02:22.240
[Amit Varma]: of the trends that I've noticed and I've been thinking about more and more and

01:02:22.240 --> 01:02:26.080
[Amit Varma]: the reason I've been thinking about it more and more is that once I noticed it

01:02:26.080 --> 01:02:30.960
[Amit Varma]: it seems to be everywhere and it that's basically the dissipation of the

01:02:30.960 --> 01:02:35.080
[Amit Varma]: mainstream and the complete decentralization in a number of

01:02:35.080 --> 01:02:39.480
[Amit Varma]: industries one of them obviously journalism because in the 90s you have

01:02:39.480 --> 01:02:43.840
[Amit Varma]: this big behemoth mainstream media houses and you've got a consensus on the

01:02:43.840 --> 01:02:48.040
[Amit Varma]: truth and everything is coming from there and in the way that you just

01:02:48.040 --> 01:02:51.720
[Amit Varma]: describe it like what you're describing really seems to be a really top-down

01:02:51.720 --> 01:02:55.240
[Amit Varma]: central thing that is happening you see the blindness of people with narrow

01:02:55.240 --> 01:02:59.560
[Amit Varma]: visions and they're not really catering to the whole country they've got their

01:02:59.560 --> 01:03:03.440
[Amit Varma]: preconceptions and their stereotypes and therefore the stories they want reported

01:03:03.440 --> 01:03:07.100
[Amit Varma]: come out of there and if they don't conform with the real world that's too

01:03:07.100 --> 01:03:11.240
[Amit Varma]: bad for the real world but I just feel that in media certainly the mainstream

01:03:11.240 --> 01:03:16.440
[Amit Varma]: is dissipating the way we consume stuff is coming everywhere from the edges and

01:03:16.440 --> 01:03:19.920
[Amit Varma]: it's happening across a number of margins it's happening in music for

01:03:19.920 --> 01:03:24.280
[Amit Varma]: example the East Street band's guitarist Steve Van Zandt spoke in an interview

01:03:24.280 --> 01:03:28.280
[Amit Varma]: about how rock was mainstream for you know from Beatles and Dylan turning

01:03:28.280 --> 01:03:31.920
[Amit Varma]: electric to Nirvana and now there's no mainstream anymore everything is all

01:03:31.920 --> 01:03:34.960
[Amit Varma]: over the place you see that happening maybe with nation states that nation

01:03:34.960 --> 01:03:38.600
[Amit Varma]: states you know their control is dissipating because individuals are

01:03:38.600 --> 01:03:43.520
[Amit Varma]: empowered with technologies and so on now it strikes me that in the context of

01:03:43.520 --> 01:03:46.600
[Amit Varma]: the news minute I've even heard in previous interviews where you've spoken

01:03:46.600 --> 01:03:50.560
[Amit Varma]: about you've referred to it or the whoever was speaking to you has referred

01:03:50.560 --> 01:03:54.240
[Amit Varma]: to it as a niche and I don't actually think it's a niche I don't think it's a

01:03:54.240 --> 01:03:58.720
[Amit Varma]: niche because I think what will happen over a period of time is not that these

01:03:58.720 --> 01:04:02.840
[Amit Varma]: big behemoths in the center will survive and there'll be just a whole bunch of

01:04:02.840 --> 01:04:06.760
[Amit Varma]: niches which feels like a very condescending way of putting it I just

01:04:06.760 --> 01:04:11.960
[Amit Varma]: think that news will get more and more decentralized more and more local where

01:04:11.960 --> 01:04:15.400
[Amit Varma]: you you might have a channel for the south and then you might have a channel

01:04:15.400 --> 01:04:20.440
[Amit Varma]: for Karnataka and then you might have something for the Mysore area and you

01:04:20.440 --> 01:04:25.400
[Amit Varma]: know different specific ways of serving people and you kind of get more and more

01:04:25.400 --> 01:04:28.520
[Amit Varma]: decentralized and therefore the mainstream is irrelevant is that

01:04:28.520 --> 01:04:33.440
[Amit Varma]: something you've seen I mean in a sense it would appear that you almost became

01:04:33.440 --> 01:04:37.280
[Amit Varma]: an accidental participant in this it is not as if you plan this that this is a

01:04:37.280 --> 01:04:41.400
[Amit Varma]: vision this is how it's going to evolve and we obviously we'll talk about a

01:04:41.400 --> 01:04:46.360
[Amit Varma]: journey a lot more about the news minute journey but just at a broader level you

01:04:46.360 --> 01:04:49.720
[Amit Varma]: know what are your thoughts on this because I look at everything that the

01:04:49.720 --> 01:04:54.480
[Amit Varma]: mainstream media serves us and what you've described is true of any industry

01:04:54.480 --> 01:05:00.280
[Amit Varma]: right and this is also why big companies collapse so often when disruptors

01:05:00.280 --> 01:05:03.840
[Amit Varma]: come up and what often then happens is that disruptors become big

01:05:03.840 --> 01:05:07.360
[Amit Varma]: companies and they become you know elephants which can't move and then

01:05:07.360 --> 01:05:12.320
[Amit Varma]: other disruptors come but I'm not sure that it happened necessarily in you know

01:05:12.320 --> 01:05:15.840
[Amit Varma]: the way things are kind of working out so what are your sort of thoughts on that

01:05:15.840 --> 01:05:19.520
[Guest]: so I think already there is a decentralization of news there is no

01:05:19.520 --> 01:05:23.960
[Guest]: doubt about it for example the news minute we have decentralized news to a

01:05:23.960 --> 01:05:27.320
[Guest]: large extent and there are many other examples like us like there is news

01:05:27.320 --> 01:05:30.480
[Guest]: meter which does only Hyderabad news there is the queue in Malayalam which

01:05:30.480 --> 01:05:35.320
[Guest]: does only a true copy there are lots of people like that right but I am someone

01:05:35.320 --> 01:05:39.920
[Guest]: in my head I'm very clear I will not disregard or write off the mainstream

01:05:39.920 --> 01:05:43.920
[Guest]: media because there's certain utility to it considering our government sits in

01:05:43.920 --> 01:05:50.000
[Guest]: Delhi and they monitor the mainstream media most right so which is the reason

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:53.200
[Guest]: why the mainstream media has the responsibility of reporting things from

01:05:53.200 --> 01:05:57.840
[Guest]: across the country simply because they are the messengers to the government to

01:05:57.840 --> 01:06:02.760
[Guest]: people in the bureaucracy in Delhi I see no other utility for national media as

01:06:02.760 --> 01:06:08.320
[Guest]: they call it I don't see any importance of a story on any of the national

01:06:08.320 --> 01:06:14.160
[Guest]: channels unless the government has to know about it if it's a story where only

01:06:14.160 --> 01:06:17.000
[Guest]: the state government has to know about it the people have to know about it I

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:21.360
[Guest]: won't even bother like there are many times I send stories to national editor

01:06:21.360 --> 01:06:25.800
[Guest]: saying please pick it up reason being I think that okay the news minute has done

01:06:25.800 --> 01:06:29.600
[Guest]: it maybe a Deccan Chronicle has done it or somebody here has done it that's not

01:06:29.600 --> 01:06:33.880
[Guest]: enough I feel that someone from Delhi should do it because that's when you

01:06:33.880 --> 01:06:38.720
[Guest]: that's when the government listens right so only for utility purpose I am I still

01:06:38.720 --> 01:06:43.920
[Guest]: think the mainstream media should exist if our government and bureaucracy starts

01:06:43.920 --> 01:06:47.440
[Guest]: looking at all states and all media separately then fine we don't even need

01:06:47.440 --> 01:06:51.840
[Guest]: a national media right now the other problem here is that this decentralization

01:06:51.840 --> 01:06:57.520
[Guest]: that we talk is also very concentrated on in certain states and they don't have

01:06:57.520 --> 01:07:01.720
[Guest]: the resources to cover everything for example I run the news minute I have

01:07:01.720 --> 01:07:05.640
[Guest]: reporters in five states how many reporters two reporters per state can I

01:07:05.640 --> 01:07:10.200
[Guest]: write every story I cannot I am also mainly city centric because when an

01:07:10.200 --> 01:07:14.760
[Guest]: event of news happens I send people outside the city and we are actually

01:07:14.760 --> 01:07:18.520
[Guest]: better off and a lot of other people who don't even have that many resources so

01:07:18.520 --> 01:07:22.560
[Guest]: the decentralization also is not happening properly simply because lack

01:07:22.560 --> 01:07:28.600
[Guest]: of resources and nobody wants to put money in use the other problem is even

01:07:28.600 --> 01:07:32.280
[Guest]: this decentralization of news which has happened with a crop of digital sites

01:07:32.280 --> 01:07:37.640
[Guest]: coming right like the wire the quint scroll the news minute and all that is

01:07:37.640 --> 01:07:42.720
[Guest]: in English you are catering to an audience who reads English speaks in

01:07:42.720 --> 01:07:47.040
[Guest]: English understands English that is not a large section of India what is the

01:07:47.040 --> 01:07:51.320
[Guest]: decentralization of news in Tamil or Malayalam or Telugu I know only about

01:07:51.320 --> 01:07:54.760
[Guest]: the five states here I know there is independent media to some extent in

01:07:54.760 --> 01:07:59.520
[Guest]: Kerala but even that is not very well read the reach is not very good

01:07:59.520 --> 01:08:05.800
[Guest]: Tamil there's hardly anything Telugu no absolutely no Karnataka very few sites

01:08:05.800 --> 01:08:10.600
[Guest]: so this decentralization is also very English specific it has not happened in

01:08:10.600 --> 01:08:15.600
[Guest]: a large way in other languages so even if the word niche perhaps is looking is

01:08:15.600 --> 01:08:19.080
[Guest]: a bit condescending as you said the point is we have not even built those

01:08:19.080 --> 01:08:24.360
[Guest]: niches we have not built we have not been successful if news minutes started

01:08:24.360 --> 01:08:28.520
[Guest]: in 2014 at that time a lot of websites started I mean we are just six months

01:08:28.520 --> 01:08:32.840
[Guest]: before our scroll started six months after us the wire started but beyond

01:08:32.840 --> 01:08:38.440
[Guest]: that what have we seen like I head digipub an association of digital media

01:08:38.440 --> 01:08:45.840
[Guest]: organizations we have 90 members I have not heard of at least 16 that and I am

01:08:45.840 --> 01:08:50.480
[Guest]: in the industry and when I look at those websites I know that they are just SEO

01:08:50.480 --> 01:08:55.080
[Guest]: based and they put whatever stuff that's it other than that we have a few new

01:08:55.080 --> 01:08:59.240
[Guest]: ones recently like article 14 which are doing very specific very specialized

01:08:59.240 --> 01:09:03.760
[Guest]: work right so in a huge country like India if you want to decentralize news

01:09:03.760 --> 01:09:07.680
[Guest]: also we need more people to come and support these organizations we need more

01:09:07.680 --> 01:09:13.400
[Guest]: organizations to come up it's only that why did a lot of Dalit thinkers for

01:09:13.400 --> 01:09:17.280
[Guest]: example start Velli Vada and so many other websites because there was no

01:09:17.280 --> 01:09:21.920
[Guest]: void no platform was giving their voice as it is needed to be given which is why

01:09:21.920 --> 01:09:25.960
[Guest]: they started it right they these are different things but I'm saying at some

01:09:25.960 --> 01:09:29.200
[Guest]: point of time we will need all these voices to come together also and become

01:09:29.200 --> 01:09:32.760
[Guest]: one powerful voice which which the government cannot ignore them which

01:09:32.760 --> 01:09:36.080
[Guest]: which even people sitting in Delhi will know okay this is happening so

01:09:36.080 --> 01:09:41.360
[Guest]: decentralization I feel is a very small exercise till now it's not happened to a

01:09:41.360 --> 01:09:46.080
[Guest]: large extent it has to happen more and more only then will it mean anything I

01:09:46.080 --> 01:09:50.280
[Guest]: mean we have seen the kind of resistance which only a like 10 or 15 sites can put

01:09:50.280 --> 01:09:54.160
[Guest]: up to a new story which is evolving we understand the perspective that they can

01:09:54.160 --> 01:09:58.440
[Guest]: bring to the table imagine if that's a huge exercise and there are people in

01:09:58.440 --> 01:10:02.280
[Guest]: various languages contributing to that how much it will change the landscape of

01:10:02.280 --> 01:10:08.040
[Amit Varma]: our country so I want to double click on a bunch of things here and and the first

01:10:08.040 --> 01:10:11.800
[Amit Varma]: of them that I find very interesting is that you spoke about how the mainstream

01:10:11.800 --> 01:10:16.120
[Amit Varma]: media is relevant only because you know people in Delhi will then listen to your

01:10:16.120 --> 01:10:20.880
[Amit Varma]: politicians or people in power and so on and so forth and I've always sort of

01:10:20.880 --> 01:10:24.520
[Amit Varma]: thought of journalism as a whole purpose is that you're catering to people you

01:10:24.520 --> 01:10:27.760
[Amit Varma]: know and of course you speak truth to power and of course you afflict the

01:10:27.760 --> 01:10:31.480
[Amit Varma]: comfortable and all of that is there but essentially your audience is the people

01:10:31.480 --> 01:10:36.200
[Amit Varma]: at large and you're giving them what knowledge perspectives news first draft

01:10:36.200 --> 01:10:41.240
[Amit Varma]: of history all of that I never thought of one purpose of journalism as being

01:10:41.240 --> 01:10:45.080
[Amit Varma]: actually speaking to the government in power so they make a difference and I

01:10:45.080 --> 01:10:49.000
[Amit Varma]: would actually have thought that if that worked it would work before you go to

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:53.200
[Amit Varma]: the people first and then if there is a bottom of expression then you know the

01:10:53.200 --> 01:10:56.160
[Amit Varma]: people in power will actually change something why will they change something

01:10:56.160 --> 01:10:59.760
[Amit Varma]: just because a journalist is after something but obviously I'm wrong

01:10:59.760 --> 01:11:03.840
[Guest]: because you've said that that's how it works out so can you see national media

01:11:03.840 --> 01:11:07.960
[Guest]: I mean the TV media I'm not talking about newspapers at all but can you give

01:11:07.960 --> 01:11:13.160
[Amit Varma]: me an example of how coverage by mainstream media of something especially

01:11:13.160 --> 01:11:17.080
[Amit Varma]: if it's in the south has actually changed anything at the level of someone

01:11:17.080 --> 01:11:20.080
[Amit Varma]: in government paying attention and doing something about it everything for

01:11:20.080 --> 01:11:24.000
[Guest]: example if there's a flood coverage right and there is continuous coverage

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:28.200
[Guest]: of a flood on a national TV channel the point is someone sitting in Delhi is

01:11:28.200 --> 01:11:32.920
[Guest]: going to think okay at least for perception basis we have to give this

01:11:32.920 --> 01:11:38.960
[Guest]: we had ensure that this many NDRF people or boats are given they would do it

01:11:38.960 --> 01:11:41.800
[Guest]: otherwise also but they may do a little bit more because there is sustained

01:11:41.800 --> 01:11:46.280
[Guest]: coverage right for example when the Sri Lankan war was going on at that time

01:11:46.280 --> 01:11:49.400
[Guest]: there was a lot of focus on the Sri Lankan war and what the Tamil parties

01:11:49.400 --> 01:11:52.960
[Guest]: were saying and a lot of things which happened in that process were reactions

01:11:52.960 --> 01:11:58.840
[Guest]: from the government and if M Karunanidhi sitting on Marina Beach and

01:11:58.840 --> 01:12:03.800
[Guest]: doing that whole whatever half-day protest that he did was not covered a

01:12:03.800 --> 01:12:07.760
[Guest]: lot by all the national channels the government can still try to turn a blind

01:12:07.760 --> 01:12:11.320
[Guest]: eye but all cameras are focused on him right other than the fact that he is

01:12:11.320 --> 01:12:15.480
[Guest]: sitting there that is important the fact that the media coverage is adding to it

01:12:15.480 --> 01:12:20.920
[Guest]: so you know in many ways Delhi channels covering a certain thing adds value to

01:12:20.920 --> 01:12:25.120
[Guest]: it I'm not talking about Indian Express or the Hindustan Times or newspapers at

01:12:25.120 --> 01:12:29.520
[Guest]: all they do their job much more properly they go to the people

01:12:29.520 --> 01:12:33.320
[Guest]: they tell their stories TV channels have stopped doing that long back so I'm not

01:12:33.320 --> 01:12:36.800
[Guest]: looking at them in that way at all to tell the story of the person I am only

01:12:36.800 --> 01:12:41.680
[Guest]: looking at utility if a story is told will the government react to it if they

01:12:41.680 --> 01:12:45.960
[Guest]: carry the story for example there is a ship which has been captured by the

01:12:45.960 --> 01:12:49.840
[Guest]: Houthi rebels in Yemen there are seven Indians on it we don't even know who the

01:12:49.840 --> 01:12:53.400
[Guest]: seventh Indian is we know about six Indians newspapers have written about it

01:12:53.400 --> 01:12:57.080
[Guest]: we have written about it we have written a very detailed copy on how there is

01:12:57.080 --> 01:13:01.040
[Guest]: absolutely no word and this is a problem between Saudi Arabia and the rebels and

01:13:01.040 --> 01:13:04.840
[Guest]: Indians are just caught in between because it was Saudi Arabian ship which

01:13:04.840 --> 01:13:08.160
[Guest]: apparently had arms and ammunitions which the crew did not know about but

01:13:08.160 --> 01:13:11.640
[Guest]: Saudi saying he did not have arms and ammunition it was only a hospital

01:13:11.640 --> 01:13:15.400
[Guest]: equipment and the rebels have planted the arms and ammunition we don't know

01:13:15.400 --> 01:13:18.760
[Guest]: who's saying the truth that it's Saudi or the rebels my simple point amid this

01:13:18.760 --> 01:13:22.840
[Guest]: today let's say if a national channel like Times Now decides to take it up and

01:13:22.840 --> 01:13:27.720
[Guest]: three days there on a campaign saying let's do something for the Indians who

01:13:27.720 --> 01:13:33.680
[Guest]: are who are caught by these rebels the government may do something just for

01:13:33.680 --> 01:13:37.320
[Guest]: eyeballs but it's fine they will do they can force them to do they have the

01:13:37.320 --> 01:13:41.240
[Guest]: capability to do it they stop telling people stories long ago that is their

01:13:41.240 --> 01:13:45.560
[Guest]: problem but if they do they can make the government listen

01:13:45.560 --> 01:13:49.560
[Amit Varma]: yeah and one of the things that points to what you're saying is that then

01:13:49.560 --> 01:13:53.440
[Amit Varma]: governance is seriously broken if for government to act on a matter that is

01:13:53.440 --> 01:13:56.320
[Amit Varma]: important you actually need the media to bring it to their attention and all

01:13:56.320 --> 01:14:02.120
[Amit Varma]: these extraneous sort of considerations to begin to matter my next question is

01:14:02.120 --> 01:14:08.920
[Amit Varma]: that you know I keep meeting people who keep praising the work that people like

01:14:08.920 --> 01:14:13.640
[Amit Varma]: you do or scroll do or news laundry does and so on and so forth right I have felt

01:14:13.640 --> 01:14:16.760
[Amit Varma]: and obviously I would be biased because I would be meeting to be you know

01:14:16.760 --> 01:14:21.480
[Amit Varma]: listening to people who would share similar values to mine but I have felt

01:14:21.480 --> 01:14:25.280
[Amit Varma]: and in the evolution of my podcast I have certainly felt there are people who

01:14:25.280 --> 01:14:28.800
[Amit Varma]: crave depth there are people who definitely would crave the kind of

01:14:28.800 --> 01:14:33.240
[Amit Varma]: reportage that you do and there isn't enough of it out there my good friend

01:14:33.240 --> 01:14:37.240
[Amit Varma]: Prem Panicker once described what the media does as going a mile wide and an

01:14:37.240 --> 01:14:41.680
[Amit Varma]: inch deep and maybe they have to because of the imperatives of the day whether it

01:14:41.680 --> 01:14:46.080
[Amit Varma]: is you know they've paid huge license fees and they're too dependent on

01:14:46.080 --> 01:14:50.000
[Amit Varma]: advertising so you go for the lowest common denominator and so on and so

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:54.880
[Amit Varma]: forth and therefore people crave depth I see this with the five-hour

01:14:54.880 --> 01:14:58.680
[Amit Varma]: conversations I have for example where typically five years ago I would have

01:14:58.680 --> 01:15:01.920
[Amit Varma]: assumed no one has five hours everybody has a short retention span blah blah

01:15:01.920 --> 01:15:06.800
[Amit Varma]: blah but no the engagement is off the charts similarly I see the love that

01:15:06.800 --> 01:15:10.560
[Amit Varma]: people have for the kind of work that you guys do and by you guys I mean the

01:15:10.560 --> 01:15:14.840
[Amit Varma]: News Minute and the handful of others and we hardly need to name them so my

01:15:14.840 --> 01:15:20.600
[Amit Varma]: question is that what sense do you get of the hunger that there is because what

01:15:20.600 --> 01:15:24.720
[Amit Varma]: I have seen happening in the creator economy worldwide over the last in a

01:15:24.720 --> 01:15:28.520
[Amit Varma]: sense I'll include you in the creator economy and if you want me to double

01:15:28.520 --> 01:15:32.480
[Amit Varma]: click on that I can but I'd include you in that and what I've seen happening

01:15:32.480 --> 01:15:36.280
[Amit Varma]: over the last decade or so in the creator economy is that there is a lag

01:15:36.280 --> 01:15:42.760
[Amit Varma]: between the hunger and the monetization of that but that lag is always sooner or

01:15:42.760 --> 01:15:47.200
[Amit Varma]: later covered so there might be you know that there was this phase where creators

01:15:47.200 --> 01:15:52.000
[Amit Varma]: began to connect directly with audiences but couldn't monetize it yet so you'd

01:15:52.000 --> 01:15:56.200
[Amit Varma]: have to go through you know via means like advertisers or sponsors but then

01:15:56.200 --> 01:16:00.200
[Amit Varma]: there came a moment where they actually began to monetize it and it actually

01:16:00.200 --> 01:16:04.600
[Amit Varma]: kind of began to make sense like I recorded with Akar Patel two or three

01:16:04.600 --> 01:16:08.360
[Amit Varma]: days ago though that episode might come out after this and he was talking about

01:16:08.360 --> 01:16:11.920
[Amit Varma]: how back in the day in some of the places that he worked big media house

01:16:11.920 --> 01:16:15.240
[Amit Varma]: would have three four hundred or thousand I forget what it is but it's a

01:16:15.240 --> 01:16:21.400
[Amit Varma]: big number reporters in each state right and his point was that if you look at

01:16:21.400 --> 01:16:27.080
[Amit Varma]: the financial models today it's not feasible for you know anyone to actually

01:16:27.080 --> 01:16:31.840
[Amit Varma]: put money into that kind of reportage and that would certainly apply more to

01:16:31.840 --> 01:16:37.680
[Amit Varma]: you know young startups like all of you so what is your sense of that hunger

01:16:37.680 --> 01:16:41.040
[Amit Varma]: like at some point you know how the future will evolve we don't know it's

01:16:41.040 --> 01:16:44.760
[Amit Varma]: unknown unknowns but what is that sense of that hunger and the appreciation that

01:16:44.760 --> 01:16:50.360
[Amit Varma]: you get because my sense is that your absolute numbers may not be mind

01:16:50.360 --> 01:16:55.640
[Amit Varma]: blowingly massive but of the numbers that you do have the engagement would be

01:16:55.640 --> 01:17:00.760
[Amit Varma]: far greater the loyalty would be far greater that personal connect would be

01:17:00.760 --> 01:17:04.080
[Amit Varma]: far greater I mean that's another thing I noticed I was you know looking at your

01:17:04.080 --> 01:17:07.320
[Amit Varma]: Instagram and I think one of the things that really works for you like when you

01:17:07.320 --> 01:17:12.000
[Amit Varma]: put up that eight image thing on the income tax rates and all that and there

01:17:12.000 --> 01:17:16.400
[Amit Varma]: is that sense of for everyone who reads your site there is that sense of

01:17:16.400 --> 01:17:21.760
[Amit Varma]: personal engagement that these people are part of my sort of part of my world

01:17:21.760 --> 01:17:25.440
[Amit Varma]: these are my people they're doing it for me whereas with mainstream media with

01:17:25.440 --> 01:17:29.560
[Amit Varma]: big media it's just a complete disconnect you know even people even

01:17:29.560 --> 01:17:34.920
[Amit Varma]: fans of or not as you pronounce that in such a charming way or not even you know

01:17:34.920 --> 01:17:39.720
[Amit Varma]: fans of or not who might support him and you know they'll do jingoism with him

01:17:39.720 --> 01:17:43.720
[Amit Varma]: won't feel that personal connect with him that if he sneezes one day they'll

01:17:43.720 --> 01:17:48.080
[Guest]: be like shit does he have a cold yeah I'm just thinking of on up sneezing and

01:17:48.080 --> 01:17:55.200
[Guest]: having a cold but see I think this is a dilemma I face right first what you said

01:17:55.200 --> 01:18:00.200
[Guest]: um the financial models the revenue models we have been around for eight years so

01:18:00.200 --> 01:18:03.600
[Guest]: have news on news on has been around for ten years it's the I think longest

01:18:03.600 --> 01:18:07.600
[Guest]: running site but it was started by someone like Madhu Trehan who and Abhinandan

01:18:07.600 --> 01:18:12.040
[Guest]: who both have had experience running something it's not like me I was just a

01:18:12.040 --> 01:18:18.040
[Guest]: mid-level mid-career journalist who did not want back to go back to TV that's it

01:18:18.040 --> 01:18:22.880
[Guest]: so all of us are figuring out our revenue models I think for example the

01:18:22.880 --> 01:18:28.680
[Guest]: wire or the alt news which are not non-profit they they have better revenue

01:18:28.680 --> 01:18:33.400
[Guest]: models because people can donate to them and the news laundry for example is a

01:18:33.400 --> 01:18:37.400
[Guest]: very loyal set of readers who contribute we are a little bit different because we

01:18:37.400 --> 01:18:41.560
[Guest]: also cover news therefore to make people pay for it is very difficult I mean

01:18:41.560 --> 01:18:46.360
[Guest]: whenever I keep putting saying key you know join become a member I feel a lot

01:18:46.360 --> 01:18:49.520
[Guest]: of people believe that immediately some hundreds of people are joining in

01:18:49.520 --> 01:18:53.440
[Guest]: thousands of people are members it's not true it's very difficult to move

01:18:53.440 --> 01:18:58.280
[Guest]: membership forward it happens when there is a big story you get like 40 50 people

01:18:58.280 --> 01:19:02.120
[Guest]: signing in but otherwise people are not like thinking back and deciding I want

01:19:02.120 --> 01:19:06.440
[Guest]: to just give thousand two hundred rupees the news minute today they don't because

01:19:06.440 --> 01:19:11.240
[Guest]: they think this news is free why should I pay for it the problem is if I stop

01:19:11.240 --> 01:19:15.120
[Guest]: the news minute tomorrow if news laundry is no longer there if the queen stops

01:19:15.120 --> 01:19:19.800
[Guest]: are you going to feel that void there as a news consumer do you think the news

01:19:19.800 --> 01:19:26.000
[Guest]: minute is important in your city in your state to tell those stories and you

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:28.480
[Guest]: should think of a scenario where the news minute is not there and if it

01:19:28.480 --> 01:19:31.840
[Guest]: continues like this a news minute may not actually be there so which is why

01:19:31.840 --> 01:19:34.760
[Guest]: the readers have to step in now that's the model which all of us are working

01:19:34.760 --> 01:19:39.280
[Guest]: with where the reader feels the necessity and reader fee supports the

01:19:39.280 --> 01:19:44.360
[Guest]: organization but that is also scalable only to a certain extent right it cannot

01:19:44.360 --> 01:19:48.560
[Guest]: it's not scalable to an extent where from a 40% organization I can become 80

01:19:48.560 --> 01:19:53.880
[Guest]: and I can have reporters in all two tier cities I can have investigating report

01:19:53.880 --> 01:19:57.520
[Guest]: investigative reporter somebody looks only at quotes etc beats these are all

01:19:57.520 --> 01:20:01.640
[Guest]: sacrifices we make we don't have beat reporters we don't reporters in second

01:20:01.640 --> 01:20:05.960
[Guest]: tier cities because we don't have the strength for it right so can readers

01:20:05.960 --> 01:20:10.960
[Guest]: paying bridge that gap it cannot so then what have we all realized that look we

01:20:10.960 --> 01:20:15.640
[Guest]: can only make this much money with that we can simply support our organization

01:20:15.640 --> 01:20:21.480
[Guest]: let's just be very powerful in the stories we write but I fear that in the

01:20:21.480 --> 01:20:24.520
[Guest]: last two or three years though we all have become better in storytelling we

01:20:24.520 --> 01:20:28.520
[Guest]: are telling very important stories we're still catering to the same crowd again

01:20:28.520 --> 01:20:34.280
[Guest]: and again now there are two reasons why one we are all English websites we are

01:20:34.280 --> 01:20:37.760
[Guest]: writing in English our videos are in English it is catering to the same crowd

01:20:37.760 --> 01:20:42.040
[Guest]: now of course wire and others have Hindi so they reach out to another crowd but

01:20:42.040 --> 01:20:46.520
[Guest]: for a South Indian here we are a very English website right so one you have to

01:20:46.520 --> 01:20:50.720
[Guest]: start in languages now if the all the websites I talked about are liberal

01:20:50.720 --> 01:20:55.240
[Guest]: progressive they have a certain take on issues they've talked for environment

01:20:55.240 --> 01:20:58.800
[Guest]: for climate change etc they passionately believe in different different things in

01:20:58.800 --> 01:21:05.560
[Guest]: democracy but if you really want to make a change one you have to scale by scale

01:21:05.560 --> 01:21:08.760
[Guest]: I mean you don't have to do many different things I don't want to become

01:21:08.760 --> 01:21:14.840
[Guest]: an NDTV where recipes are there you know something happened in Japan some girl

01:21:14.840 --> 01:21:18.560
[Guest]: sang beautifully that story is also there in China somebody fell in a

01:21:18.560 --> 01:21:23.440
[Guest]: pothole that story is also there plus I because that's just traffic I never want

01:21:23.440 --> 01:21:26.880
[Guest]: to be like that even if I have a lot of money I don't want to be like that I

01:21:26.880 --> 01:21:31.680
[Guest]: want to be the news minute if I have two reporters now I want to have six

01:21:31.680 --> 01:21:37.040
[Guest]: reporters in a state but I also want to scale in the sense that I want to reach

01:21:37.040 --> 01:21:42.320
[Guest]: more audiences now the problem in digital is also that you have to invest a

01:21:42.320 --> 01:21:47.280
[Guest]: little bit of money to even reach people you have to invest new SEO at one point

01:21:47.280 --> 01:21:51.120
[Guest]: of time all of us were spending so much money on Facebook thankfully that has

01:21:51.120 --> 01:21:55.600
[Guest]: stopped I mean imagine on Facebook for your post to be read you have to boost

01:21:55.600 --> 01:22:01.040
[Guest]: it otherwise Facebook will not shown that algorithm now we are like screw

01:22:01.040 --> 01:22:04.760
[Guest]: this we are not going to do this we don't want people to read like that if

01:22:04.760 --> 01:22:09.440
[Guest]: it is organically doing well it can but I can tell you Amit the number of

01:22:09.440 --> 01:22:15.600
[Guest]: stories which should be read by 3 lakh 4 lakh 5 lakh people because of the fact

01:22:15.600 --> 01:22:21.040
[Guest]: is important it's only read by 10,000 people why because Google algorithm has

01:22:21.040 --> 01:22:25.080
[Guest]: something called showcase now where they have signed contracts with all these big

01:22:25.080 --> 01:22:28.560
[Guest]: media houses in India and Facebook literally does not show anything on

01:22:28.560 --> 01:22:32.840
[Guest]: their algorithm the small sites are suffering more and more so we are

01:22:32.840 --> 01:22:36.680
[Guest]: actually becoming smaller and smaller when it comes to our readership right

01:22:36.680 --> 01:22:41.320
[Guest]: because none of us will write about somebody's divorce and what is happening

01:22:41.320 --> 01:22:46.680
[Guest]: in that or we will not stoop to writing about like what the Times of India does

01:22:46.680 --> 01:22:50.240
[Guest]: five bikinis somebody wore in the beach we are not doing that we are not scaling

01:22:50.240 --> 01:22:54.800
[Guest]: in that way at all but technology is stopping us to one extent money is

01:22:54.800 --> 01:22:59.800
[Guest]: stopping us to the other to another extent so what I want in my vision is

01:22:59.800 --> 01:23:04.360
[Guest]: money either from the readers or you know there are people who have money in

01:23:04.360 --> 01:23:08.800
[Guest]: India who realize that we need a vibrant democracy we have to invest in media or

01:23:08.800 --> 01:23:11.840
[Guest]: ten years later we can twiddle our thumbs and say oh my god we didn't do

01:23:11.840 --> 01:23:16.680
[Guest]: anything about it so either they put in money in the media and we have to break

01:23:16.680 --> 01:23:21.960
[Guest]: away from this English dominance here we have to start in languages all this

01:23:21.960 --> 01:23:26.960
[Guest]: entire exercise means nothing if you are going to be only catering to the

01:23:26.960 --> 01:23:31.080
[Guest]: English reading audiences you are not touching the pulse of India if so for me

01:23:31.080 --> 01:23:36.360
[Guest]: as an entrepreneur I mean I classify myself as an entrepreneur only in very

01:23:36.360 --> 01:23:41.800
[Guest]: few conversations I'm classifying myself for this answer I feel all of us have to

01:23:41.800 --> 01:23:47.320
[Guest]: become scalable I do know that when we discuss business plans everybody in my

01:23:47.320 --> 01:23:51.440
[Guest]: office and others tell me it's okay you need to have loyal readers I want loyal

01:23:51.440 --> 01:23:54.600
[Guest]: readers I'm not saying no but I also want more people to read it because I

01:23:54.600 --> 01:23:59.760
[Guest]: think what we write is important and for that scalability unfortunately you need

01:23:59.760 --> 01:24:06.640
[Guest]: either money or you just need algorithms to work for you right and third thing

01:24:06.640 --> 01:24:11.520
[Guest]: is languages which is my dream forever but it's never been happening. So I want

01:24:11.520 --> 01:24:15.400
[Amit Varma]: to double click on each of these big themes and and the first one is that you

01:24:15.400 --> 01:24:20.200
[Amit Varma]: you know what essentially saying is that sure there might be people who have the

01:24:20.200 --> 01:24:23.800
[Amit Varma]: hunger for such news and sure they might even be willing to pay for it but how do

01:24:23.800 --> 01:24:27.920
[Amit Varma]: we reach them and and the constraint is their money how do we scale and there

01:24:27.920 --> 01:24:33.240
[Amit Varma]: also I feel like that there is a natural dilemma there is a trade-off because the

01:24:33.240 --> 01:24:36.120
[Amit Varma]: more you try to scale the more you compromise and the question then comes

01:24:36.120 --> 01:24:39.920
[Amit Varma]: is where do you draw the line you can of course just do a thousand stories about

01:24:39.920 --> 01:24:43.920
[Amit Varma]: children falling into wells and all kinds of nonsense and get some numbers

01:24:43.920 --> 01:24:48.480
[Amit Varma]: but where do you draw the line and I imagine for every news organization like

01:24:48.480 --> 01:24:53.800
[Amit Varma]: yours then that where to draw the line the answer to that would come from some

01:24:53.800 --> 01:24:58.520
[Amit Varma]: core values or core beliefs that you have some clear idea of yourself that

01:24:58.520 --> 01:25:03.920
[Amit Varma]: this is what we are this is why we exist this is what we do we wanted to get to

01:25:03.920 --> 01:25:07.720
[Amit Varma]: all the readers who might value this and what are we willing to do to get there

01:25:07.720 --> 01:25:11.560
[Amit Varma]: like how does one then reconcile this because you're right that there is no

01:25:11.560 --> 01:25:15.920
[Amit Varma]: point staying in a small idealistic space with a handful of reporters where

01:25:15.920 --> 01:25:20.040
[Amit Varma]: the good work is not reaching the people who would appreciate the good work and

01:25:20.040 --> 01:25:24.280
[Amit Varma]: fund more of it but at the same time what do you have to do to get there I

01:25:24.280 --> 01:25:29.320
[Amit Varma]: mean you know that's like you've obviously been living this process for

01:25:29.320 --> 01:25:33.760
[Guest]: the last few years if I had figured that out then I will be having news minute in

01:25:33.760 --> 01:25:38.400
[Guest]: many languages so technically I've not figured it out but see when I say I want

01:25:38.400 --> 01:25:42.520
[Guest]: the things to reach more people it's not only because I want them to become a

01:25:42.520 --> 01:25:46.840
[Guest]: loyal reader or I want them to pay for news the hijab row for example I keep

01:25:46.840 --> 01:25:49.320
[Guest]: going back to it because that's the most current thing which we are covering

01:25:49.320 --> 01:25:54.080
[Guest]: right if you see the kind of coverage in Kannada media especially in Kannada

01:25:54.080 --> 01:25:59.560
[Guest]: television you will be appalled the kind of things that say they will put Isis

01:25:59.560 --> 01:26:03.640
[Guest]: behind the girls the five girls in the hijab are shown and they will have

01:26:03.640 --> 01:26:08.240
[Guest]: headlines saying does Isis have a hand in the hijab row like what proof do you

01:26:08.240 --> 01:26:12.200
[Guest]: have to say any of this that is the kind of messaging going to the larger

01:26:12.200 --> 01:26:17.480
[Guest]: population the news minute is read by let's say one story we do like we had

01:26:17.480 --> 01:26:21.200
[Guest]: this fantastic story by my colleague Prajwal and then my another colleague

01:26:21.200 --> 01:26:25.120
[Guest]: Pooja Prasanna they both wrote about how the saffron shawl protest was not an

01:26:25.120 --> 01:26:32.000
[Guest]: organic thing it was very well organized right it was viral for a lot of people

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:37.440
[Guest]: but in absolute numbers maybe 50,000 people who read the story right it was

01:26:37.440 --> 01:26:40.800
[Guest]: really viral and Google algorithm had picked up maybe that number would have

01:26:40.800 --> 01:26:44.480
[Guest]: gone to one or one and a half lakhs but I'm saying the stories we're saying are

01:26:44.480 --> 01:26:48.800
[Guest]: important it doesn't matter if people eventually pay for it oh I don't care

01:26:48.800 --> 01:26:53.040
[Guest]: about that but I think to counter the narratives which are being spread by a

01:26:53.040 --> 01:26:58.200
[Guest]: lot of toxic mainstream media it is very important that we become scalable but

01:26:58.200 --> 01:27:03.600
[Guest]: unfortunately technology and lack of resource is pulling us down and it is

01:27:03.600 --> 01:27:08.400
[Guest]: continuously happening like we have a lot of meetings and discussions I mean I

01:27:08.400 --> 01:27:12.440
[Guest]: speak to Abhinandan I speak to a lot of people on a on a weekly basis of

01:27:12.440 --> 01:27:16.960
[Guest]: whatever there is no perfect solution to this all of us are becoming more and

01:27:16.960 --> 01:27:21.160
[Guest]: more I think we're just like in our own cocoons where okay I have loyal

01:27:21.160 --> 01:27:24.240
[Guest]: readers a news minute I will keep catering to them the news laundry is

01:27:24.240 --> 01:27:28.000
[Guest]: loved by this many people I will grow that number slowly but I'm not thinking

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:30.720
[Guest]: like that I'm saying more people should read the news laundry more people should

01:27:30.720 --> 01:27:34.480
[Guest]: know the news minute or the wire it should not be the same people right

01:27:34.480 --> 01:27:39.480
[Guest]: because there are people out there who are ready to read new viewpoints accept

01:27:39.480 --> 01:27:42.840
[Guest]: new viewpoints and understand the world better see I don't want to classify

01:27:42.840 --> 01:27:47.200
[Guest]: everybody is black and white saying or you know you're a sanghi or a non sanghi

01:27:47.200 --> 01:27:51.120
[Guest]: or this you're that no there are a lot of people who don't actually have a good

01:27:51.120 --> 01:27:56.120
[Guest]: idea of what's happening and if they are told that look Isis is not behind the

01:27:56.120 --> 01:27:59.560
[Guest]: hijab bro there is nothing like that there's no proof the Kannada channels

01:27:59.560 --> 01:28:03.560
[Guest]: are lying to you if somebody tells them that they're the intelligence to accept

01:28:03.560 --> 01:28:07.880
[Guest]: that argument but we are not reaching them because we don't have the resources

01:28:07.880 --> 01:28:13.640
[Guest]: to reach them all the algorithms goes with us so what is my solution my

01:28:13.640 --> 01:28:18.640
[Guest]: solution is scaling up in different ways I don't know see I tell everyone to for

01:28:18.640 --> 01:28:22.480
[Guest]: example I know that for example all news ask for donations wire ask for donations

01:28:22.480 --> 01:28:26.400
[Guest]: news laundry says subscribe we say become member I I'm telling all those

01:28:26.400 --> 01:28:31.000
[Guest]: readers think of a world where this organization does not exist would that

01:28:31.000 --> 01:28:35.600
[Guest]: impact you then you decide if you want to give money to the organization close

01:28:35.600 --> 01:28:38.960
[Guest]: your eyes for two seconds and like you somebody tells you right do you really

01:28:38.960 --> 01:28:42.640
[Guest]: want his girlfriend do you will do can you imagine a life with this boyfriend

01:28:42.640 --> 01:28:48.080
[Guest]: so same way close your eyes and think for a moment do I want a scenario in the

01:28:48.080 --> 01:28:52.320
[Guest]: media where the news minute is not there or where news laundries Manisha's

01:28:52.320 --> 01:28:57.880
[Guest]: nuisance shows not there would that be a huge void for you if you feel so then

01:28:57.880 --> 01:29:02.120
[Guest]: support that organization that's the only way that we have figured out now

01:29:02.120 --> 01:29:08.120
[Guest]: but I'm really hoping that there will be some change unfortunately the nature of

01:29:08.120 --> 01:29:13.400
[Guest]: the medium is such that you know in TV you can have a great distributor like

01:29:13.400 --> 01:29:18.120
[Guest]: Sun for example in Tamil Nadu used to control distribution at one point of

01:29:18.120 --> 01:29:22.240
[Guest]: time like nobody would write a story against nobody would do a story against

01:29:22.240 --> 01:29:25.720
[Guest]: the Marans because they would be cut off on television at long back I'm not

01:29:25.720 --> 01:29:29.680
[Guest]: talking about now I this is a myth I don't know they've actually cut channels

01:29:29.680 --> 01:29:34.720
[Guest]: they have at times but it's not in a large scale but you can still build a

01:29:34.720 --> 01:29:38.040
[Guest]: very powerful distribution system your channel may suck it may have the worst

01:29:38.040 --> 01:29:42.360
[Guest]: of content you your newspaper has practically no story but if you have

01:29:42.360 --> 01:29:46.880
[Guest]: good distribution system you can still ensure that it reaches people whether

01:29:46.880 --> 01:29:50.880
[Guest]: they buy the product a newspaper has to be bought right with the TV channel

01:29:50.880 --> 01:29:55.040
[Guest]: that's not a problem but unfortunately digital doesn't work like that our

01:29:55.040 --> 01:29:59.240
[Guest]: distribution is through Google is through Facebook and little bit of

01:29:59.240 --> 01:30:03.160
[Guest]: organic stuff through people who will come or want to read a certain thing so

01:30:03.160 --> 01:30:06.160
[Guest]: when we are so dependent on those people I mean we are all trying not to be

01:30:06.160 --> 01:30:10.920
[Guest]: dependent anymore but I feel like we are going to come full circle again where we

01:30:10.920 --> 01:30:13.800
