[Amit Varma]: in the new creator economy that also plays a part but in general you know and

02:08:35.720 --> 02:08:38.880
[Amit Varma]: and this is clearly something that you've put into practice in different

02:08:38.880 --> 02:08:42.520
[Amit Varma]: ways you've thought about that and and you mentioned earlier the importance of

02:08:42.520 --> 02:08:47.840
[Amit Varma]: video so take me a little bit through your thoughts on this that you know

02:08:47.840 --> 02:08:52.280
[Amit Varma]: there are these particular forms like one of the things that I realized maybe

02:08:52.280 --> 02:08:55.880
[Amit Varma]: in just the last few months because I wasn't open to thinking about it in

02:08:55.880 --> 02:08:58.640
[Amit Varma]: those ways before that though I should have been because I was a blogger once

02:08:58.640 --> 02:09:04.800
[Amit Varma]: is that we used to think 30 years ago in terms of limited forms like if I'm

02:09:04.800 --> 02:09:08.360
[Amit Varma]: writing it's an 800 word article or a hundred thousand word book if I'm a

02:09:08.360 --> 02:09:13.400
[Amit Varma]: filmmaker it's a 24 minute TV episode or it's a 90 minute Hollywood film 180

02:09:13.400 --> 02:09:17.440
[Amit Varma]: minute Bollywood film whatever I guess for a TV person they would also be this

02:09:17.440 --> 02:09:20.880
[Amit Varma]: fixed forms that you'll have this three minute segment and the anchor cuts to

02:09:20.880 --> 02:09:24.560
[Amit Varma]: you and you take two quotes like that or whatever they'll and the problem with

02:09:24.560 --> 02:09:27.720
[Amit Varma]: thinking in those fixed forms the problem with those fixed forms to begin

02:09:27.720 --> 02:09:31.880
[Amit Varma]: with is that form determines content so when you think like that you are

02:09:31.880 --> 02:09:36.400
[Amit Varma]: constraining what you can do and I think today we've reached a time where those

02:09:36.400 --> 02:09:41.800
[Amit Varma]: constraints have to a large extent dissolved and gone away and therefore if

02:09:41.800 --> 02:09:46.560
[Amit Varma]: you think in new ways new kinds of content will emerge which equally will

02:09:46.560 --> 02:09:51.000
[Amit Varma]: shape the person producing the content the kind of work that you do maybe a

02:09:51.000 --> 02:09:55.000
[Amit Varma]: reporter will realize that I don't just have to get two quotes for an 800 word

02:09:55.000 --> 02:09:59.280
[Amit Varma]: news piece I can also write a 3,000 word newsletter I can also shoot a video I

02:09:59.280 --> 02:10:04.080
[Amit Varma]: can try and go a little deeper in different ways so and you're kind of at

02:10:04.080 --> 02:10:07.840
[Amit Varma]: the center of this as a practitioner who's figuring all this out so tell me

02:10:07.840 --> 02:10:13.640
[Guest]: a little bit about that. So I always thought of myself as a TV person eight

02:10:13.640 --> 02:10:17.400
[Guest]: years in TV I got tired of it and I somehow moved out of the medium but it's

02:10:17.400 --> 02:10:22.240
[Guest]: always there in me I want to visual right but I think the first few years of

02:10:22.240 --> 02:10:26.320
[Guest]: the news minute I consciously kept visual away from my brain because I

02:10:26.320 --> 02:10:31.680
[Guest]: wanted to also try the written word and I did not discourage anyone else from

02:10:31.680 --> 02:10:35.920
[Guest]: doing video but slowly I've also realized that TV is indeed a very

02:10:35.920 --> 02:10:40.920
[Guest]: powerful medium visual is very powerful sometimes more than the written word and

02:10:40.920 --> 02:10:45.200
[Guest]: therefore I cannot discard it I cannot think oh my god I worked eight years in

02:10:45.200 --> 02:10:49.600
[Guest]: time so I don't want to do it anymore and the problem is when you run an

02:10:49.600 --> 02:10:55.400
[Guest]: organization unfortunately the way you think is what a lot of other people

02:10:55.400 --> 02:11:00.000
[Guest]: start thinking like or mimicking so if I don't give importance to the visual

02:11:00.000 --> 02:11:03.040
[Guest]: everybody else is going to think the editor-in-chief herself doesn't believe

02:11:03.040 --> 02:11:06.080
[Guest]: in visual why should I she doesn't believe in multimedia elements right so

02:11:06.080 --> 02:11:11.160
[Guest]: we I think we saw a small downward curve for the news minute in that way for

02:11:11.160 --> 02:11:14.880
[Guest]: visual one or two years but now I'm trying to again take it up because I

02:11:14.880 --> 02:11:20.120
[Guest]: realize the value of visual and if if a written word is something which is not

02:11:20.120 --> 02:11:25.240
[Guest]: scalable like I said right it reaches only 50,000 1 lakh people and the video

02:11:25.240 --> 02:11:29.200
[Guest]: has more potential you're anyway ultimately saying the same thing here

02:11:29.200 --> 02:11:33.480
[Guest]: and there you're writing the same story in different formats so I want to pay

02:11:33.480 --> 02:11:37.880
[Guest]: more attention to video that way because I feel that more younger people people

02:11:37.880 --> 02:11:42.120
[Guest]: from various walks of life it's no longer your echo chamber there is a

02:11:42.120 --> 02:11:46.320
[Guest]: different process of people consuming videos therefore I think that it's not

02:11:46.320 --> 02:11:50.600
[Guest]: just the news minute most news organizations are now tilting towards it

02:11:50.600 --> 02:11:54.880
[Guest]: the Quinn for example is one which has used it quite well over the years they've

02:11:54.880 --> 02:11:59.200
[Guest]: never left taken their attention off from video the wire I see is doing more

02:11:59.200 --> 02:12:03.040
[Guest]: and more news laundries or someone who's always stuck to video right the news

02:12:03.040 --> 02:12:07.360
[Guest]: minute is one which wasn't video and then went out so I'm going back for

02:12:07.360 --> 02:12:11.520
[Guest]: everyone video is a powerful medium there's no doubt about it and I think

02:12:11.520 --> 02:12:16.760
[Guest]: younger people consume video more so if you want to reach out to younger people

02:12:16.760 --> 02:12:22.040
[Guest]: I think you have to be in video sound everything and as far as journal people

02:12:22.040 --> 02:12:26.480
[Guest]: who are journalists I doubt there are any journalists who now think that I'm

02:12:26.480 --> 02:12:30.160
[Guest]: a print journalist I will only write when print journalists go to a place

02:12:30.160 --> 02:12:34.760
[Guest]: they are asked to record videos or they asked to take bites so no one can their

02:12:34.760 --> 02:12:39.120
[Guest]: vision cannot be narrow anymore I think those days are gone but the problem is

02:12:39.120 --> 02:12:42.960
[Guest]: that it's not enough that you envision yourself as a journalist who will go to

02:12:42.960 --> 02:12:46.200
[Guest]: the ground and say okay I will also shoot a bite I will also write my story

02:12:46.200 --> 02:12:51.000
[Guest]: you need talent in it everybody can shoot a bite but can you construct a

02:12:51.000 --> 02:12:55.560
[Guest]: story around it so that is where we are we have a problem we are just letting

02:12:55.560 --> 02:12:59.760
[Guest]: everybody shoot videos and put it out and there's no quality at the end of it

02:12:59.760 --> 02:13:03.520
[Guest]: which is why organizations now have to take a call that I want quality also I

02:13:03.520 --> 02:13:07.920
[Guest]: just don't want quantity I I hope all this works out and we'll have quality

02:13:07.920 --> 02:13:12.160
[Guest]: videos we're going to launch a few shows I am very nervous about it because I

02:13:12.160 --> 02:13:15.760
[Guest]: don't know if I can do interview shows etc but everybody else says you can you

02:13:15.760 --> 02:13:19.920
[Amit Varma]: can so I'm gonna try no you absolutely should I mean you should learn a lesson

02:13:19.920 --> 02:13:24.400
[Amit Varma]: from yourself in the sense that what I often tell my writing students is that

02:13:24.400 --> 02:13:27.600
[Amit Varma]: there is a trade-off we face between getting it done and getting it right and

02:13:27.600 --> 02:13:30.520
[Amit Varma]: I think too many people paralyze themselves because they want to get it

02:13:30.520 --> 02:13:35.360
[Amit Varma]: right and they are so obsessed like you know how will I look on camera or you

02:13:35.360 --> 02:13:38.840
[Amit Varma]: know who will read me or what is you know and the imposter syndrome kicks in

02:13:38.840 --> 02:13:42.080
[Amit Varma]: and all that and my advice always is that no just get it done the only way to

02:13:42.080 --> 02:13:45.880
[Amit Varma]: get it right is to get it done again and again you might suck at the start but

02:13:45.880 --> 02:13:49.520
[Amit Varma]: you do it again and again and you'll get better and that's exactly what you in

02:13:49.520 --> 02:13:53.520
[Amit Varma]: fact kind of did with the News Minute where you know it started like you said

02:13:53.520 --> 02:13:57.120
[Amit Varma]: you were aggregating a few things and it was a completely different thing and

02:13:57.120 --> 02:14:01.360
[Amit Varma]: then it sort of grew into what it is now something with a genuine vision which is

02:14:01.360 --> 02:14:04.400
[Amit Varma]: being driven in a particular way and all of that so tell me a little bit about

02:14:04.400 --> 02:14:10.120
[Amit Varma]: that journey that you know firstly why did you leave Times Now because I mean

02:14:10.120 --> 02:14:16.440
[Amit Varma]: who would leave Ornab as you pronounce it and then how did you from there how

02:14:16.440 --> 02:14:24.680
[Guest]: did the journey to the News Minute happen? So I left Ornab as you say in 2013 on

